<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jasper Sunday Sermons Offer Comfort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JASPER, Texas (AP) -- The first weekend after a white man was  
sentenced to die for the dragging death of a black man, ministers 
across this tiny east Texas timber town tried to bring comfort and 
peace to congregations made weary by the nation's scrutiny. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hate is still living and alive,'' the Rev. John D. Hardin  
assured his Mount Olive Missionary Baptist Church followers. ``But 
love has already won the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, 11 whites and one black sentenced John William King  
to death for the June slaying of James Byrd Jr., 49, found dead 
after he was dragged behind a pickup truck. 
</P>
<P>
	At St. Michael's Catholic Church, the Rev. Ron Foshage spoke of  
change and forgiveness. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to have to change,'' Foshage told his  
parishioners. ``Change our hearts and our minds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As Foshage spoke at Saturday evening mass, King's prosecutor,  
Guy James Gray, listened with bowed head, his wife, Mary, by his 
side. 
</P>
<P>
	Not 20 feet away, in another pew, sat King's ailing father,  
Ronald King. 
</P>
<P>
	``We pray for Bill King, that the Lord helps him seek  
forgiveness,'' Foshage said. ``We pray for Ronald King, who was so 
deeply humiliated and grieved. We pray for the Byrd family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Byrd's parents' church, Greater New Bethel Baptist Church,  
the Rev. Kenneth Lyons also used this week's events as a sermon. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must agree this morning that a few months ago we had a very  
horrible tragedy occur in our town. It was an event that shocked 
Jasper, the country and the world,'' Lyons said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The men who committed this crime meant it for evil against a  
black man, but God meant it for good,'' Lyons said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Jasper United Pentecostal Church, Senior Pastor Malcolm  
Seal didn't discuss the trial in his sermon Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Several members of King's family attend the church, and Seal  
said it was sufficient that he preached about the murder right 
after it happened. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're human beings, and I'm concerned for their welfare as  
well. They didn't commit any crime. They're victims,'' Seal said. 
</P>
<P>
	Trials for King's co-defendants -- Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31,  
and Shawn Allen Berry, 24, have not been scheduled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
