<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Feb. 28, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Body of Missing Mass. Boy Found  
</P>
<P>
	NORTON, Mass. (AP) -- The body of 9-year-old Corey Anderson, who  
disappeared Thursday while looking for his dog in a snowstorm, was 
found today next to a shallow stream near his family's home. Rescue 
crews admitted that after four days of searching -- and temperatures 
in the 20s -- chances of finding the fourth-grader alive were not 
good. A search party made the grim discovery just before noon EST, 
police said. Rescuers used dogs, horses, boats and a helicopter 
with a heat-seeking infrared device to search woods, cranberry 
bogs, swamps and a partially frozen lake behind his home. 

</P>
<P>
	Nigeria Candidate To Contest Vote  
</P>
<P>
	ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- A top aide to Nigerian presidential  
candidate Olu Falae said yesterday's election was ``completely 
rigged'' and that Falae plans to contest the results. The 
announcement came as officials announced that retired Gen. Olusegun 
Obasanjo, a former military ruler seeking a civilian comeback 20 
years after leaving power, had pulled further into the lead. 
Falae's accusation follows reports by international observers of 
ballot box-stuffing and other serious voting irregularities. 

</P>
<P>
	Iraqi Sites Attacked by US Fighters  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. jets today fired on Iraqi defense sites  
after being attacked by Iraqi anti-aircraft fire. The Air Force 
F-15 fighters fired three air-to-ground missiles and dropped eight 
bombs on targets mostly around the city of Mosul, about 250 miles 
north of Baghdad, a U.S. military spokesman said. U.S. officials 
hope the bombings can encourage unrest in Iraq by portraying 
President Saddam Hussein as hapless and cornered, unable to defend 
his own territory and a danger to his own people. 

</P>
<P>
	Working Mom Absences Said Unharmful  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Children of women who work outside the home  
are not significantly harmed by their mother's absence, according 
to a study that evaluated the development and health of more than 
6,000 youngsters. The study by Elizabeth Harvey, a psychologist at 
the University of Massachusetts at Amherst, published in the March 
issue of the journal Developmental Psychology, came to a different 
conclusion than some earlier studies of the same group of children. 
The new work examined the children at a later age, 12 years old. 
One observer said the study suggests that ``hours spent away from 
home (are) not as important as the quality of parenting.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Conducts Heart Transplant  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A man in his 40s was the recipient of the first  
heart transplant in Japan in three decades today. Japan had 
effectively banned such procedures because a person couldn't be 
declared dead until the heart had stopped. That made it impossible 
to transplant the heart, liver and some other organs. But a 
controversial law passed in 1997 changed that. A 44-year-old woman 
was the first person declared brain dead since the law was passed. 
Japan's only heart transplant was done about 30 years ago, and it 
prompted criminal investigations, although the surgeon was never 
indicted. 

</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin May Stay in Hospital a Week  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Doctors say Boris Yeltsin's stomach pains have  
abated and minor bleeding in his stomach has been stopped, but that 
he will remain in the hospital for about a week. The ailing Russian 
president was readmitted yesterday for further treatment of an 
ulcer for which he was hospitalized two weeks last month. The 
68-year-old has had myriad health problems in the last three years 
since heart bypass surgery, raising doubts about his ability to 
complete his term, which ends next year. 

</P>
<P>
	Four Killed in Bombing in Lebanon  
</P>
<P>
	MARJAYOUN, Lebanon (AP) -- Four people were killed today when  
Lebanese guerrillas detonated two bombs near an Israeli convoy. The 
Iranian-backed Hezbollah group claimed responsibility for the 
bombings. Israel has occupied the zone in southern Lebanon since 
1985 in a bid to protect its northern territory from cross-border 
attacks. Hezbollah is the most active of guerrilla groups fighting 
to oust the Israelis and their militia allies. 

</P>
<P>
	Serena Williams Wins First Title  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Serena Williams won her first title on the WTA Tour  
today, beating Amelie Mauresmo 6-2, 3-6, 7-6 (7-4) in the final of 
the $520,000 Gaz de France Open. Williams, who was not seeded, beat 
two seeds en route to the final -- Nathalie Tauziat and Julie 
Halard-Decugis. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
</P>
</TEXT>
