<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 15:13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cubs Want Pennant-Type Pitcher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MESA, Ariz. (AP) -- Don't count on the Chicago Cubs acquiring a  
big-name, high-priced pitcher unless he could push them over the 
top during a pennant race, team president Andy MacPhail said 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``That type of acquisition is not beyond our realm, but it's  
more likely to happen if we are in the race and maybe the contract 
lasts a year or two as opposed to signing a 34-year-old player to a 
seven-year contract for $105 million,'' MacPhail said, referring to 
the Dodgers' deal with Kevin Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's Aug. 15 and you are two games, three games or four  
games in front and you can make a trade and take on a guy at $8 
million to finish up the year -- go. '' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs, who made the playoffs last year for the first time  
since 1989, decided to bring back most of their own free agents and 
their payroll will increase from $49 to $60 million this season 
with a veteran team. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just have a kind of bias, we like to reward our own guys,''  
MacPhail said. ``All things being equal, if we think we are just as 
good a team with a guy we had last year as opposed to paying the 
same or a little bit more for a guy who wore another uniform, we're 
predisposed to bring our guy back. 
</P>
<P>
	``We took some chances with our right fielder and that seems to  
have worked out for now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That would be National League MVP Sammy Sosa, whom the Cubs  
signed to a four-year, $42.5 million deal in June 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the Cubs' next deals could be with pitcher Kerry Wood.  
General manager Ed Lynch wants it done before the beginning of 
exhibition games this Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wood, the NL rookie of the year who struck out 20 batter in a  
game last season, made the major league minimum of $170,000 last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody who has ever seen Kerry pitch would think for a minute  
he doesn't have the potential to be something very special,'' 
MacPhail said. ``The only question on Kerry is going to be his 
durability. 
</P>
<P>
	``But that doesn't mean you don't do a multi-year deal if you  
can satisfy both parties. We want certain protections and they are 
going to want things they feel like they have to have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	MacPhail said there are no major changes planned for historic  
Wrigley Field that was built in 1914, even as more modern parks pop 
up all over baseball. The Cubs drew 2.6 million at home last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wrigley Field is a special place and we know it. It provides  
us with some insulation when you have a lousy year,'' MacPhail 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
