<HEADLINE> Orthodox Jews Protest Court Rulings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- About 25,000 Orthodox Jews prayed in the pouring  
rain Sunday to protest recent political developments in Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	The sound of Biblical psalms chanted in Hebrew echoed through  
the canyons of lower Manhattan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orthodox faithful rode by bus from as far away as Baltimore,  
but the majority came from Brooklyn to protest Israeli supreme 
court rulings that could reduce Orthodox influence over everyday 
activities in the Jewish state. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no speeches at the vigil, just a sea of bearded men  
in black hats and coats, standing separately from thousands of 
modestly dressed women reciting prayers in the various traditions 
of Syrian, Lithuanian, Polish and other Jewish groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Police watched the gathering that clogged streets over a  
12-block area, but did not interfere. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks ago, 200,000 Orthodox Jews protested in Jerusalem over  
the same grievances -- among them a recent Israeli supreme court 
edict that could allow seminary students to be drafted, and another 
challenging Orthodox control of marriage, burial and Sabbath 
travel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
