<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Convicted Minister Leads Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- One day after being convicted of  
state racketeering charges, the Rev. Henry Lyons quietly led Sunday 
morning services at his church and then went to the funeral of a 
grandmother who helped raise him. 
</P>
<P>
	The once-influential and rousing religious leader faces months  
of legal and political battles, with the National Baptist 
Convention USA considering whether to oust him as president and 
federal prosecutors gearing up for their own trial against the 
minister next month. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got to sit down with my deacons and with my wife and with  
my family and see what we're going to do,'' Lyons quietly told 
reporters after jurors found him guilty Saturday of racketeering 
and grand theft. ``I'll be doing some praying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That was his only comment to reporters as he left the courthouse  
and headed back to his congregation at Bethel Metropolitan Church 
in St. Petersburg. 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters were barred from church grounds Sunday and  
parishioners refused to comment. But church officials -- who 
wouldn't discuss the verdict or its implications -- said Lyons 
conducted morning services before leaving for his grandmother's 
funeral at Gainesville. 
</P>
<P>
	Minnie Lyons, 81, died as the five-week racketeering and grand  
theft trial against Lyons and a co-defendant wound to a close last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons, free on bail until his still-unscheduled sentencing,  
faces three to seven years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	He once was best known as a rousing preacher, sometimes  
interrupting his own sermons by shouting ``I'm doing some preaching 
now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His pleas from pulpits across the country helped greatly reduce  
the $5.4 million debt the convention accrued while building new 
headquarters in Nashville, Tenn., before he was elected president 
in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside of the church, he wielded political clout as leader of a  
group that claimed to have 8.5 million members -- the largest black 
church organization in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	That influence reached members of Congress and President  
Clinton, who spoke at convention meetings and called Lyons for 
advice when 1996 riots erupted in St. Petersburg. 
</P>
<P>
	Everything changed when fire broke out in a waterfront house  
Lyons owned with another woman. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons' wife, Deborah, said she set fires inside the $700,000  
mansion after finding a deed in her husband's briefcase showing he 
owned it with Bernice Edwards, the convention public relations 
director. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire spurred state and federal prosecutors to follow the  
trail of Lyons' money, eventually accusing him and Ms. Edwards of 
stealing more than $4 million from corporations that wanted to sell 
cemetery products, life insurance policies and credit cards to 
convention members. 
</P>
<P>
	The membership figure was a hoax and the convention may have  
closer to 1 million members, the government said. The pair duped 
the companies by promising a membership mailing list that did not 
exist, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Edwards was acquitted of racketeering, the sole charge she  
faced. 
</P>
<P>
	But she and Lyons both still face trial in federal court -- he on  
54 counts of tax evasion, extortion, money laundering and fraud; 
she on 27 similar counts. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Stuart Cureton of Greenville, S.C., said he expected  
the convention's board of directors to meet this week to discuss 
Lyons' conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's not clear how the board might proceed.  
</P>
<P>
	``We've never had this experience before,'' said Cureton, the  
convention's vice president at large and potential successor to 
Lyons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
