<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rock Group's Concert Raises $13,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLARKSVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- A free concert given by country rock  
group Sawyer Brown raised more than $13,000 to benefit victims of 
the Jan. 22 tornadoes that ravaged this city. 
</P>
<P>
	About 3,000 people attended Friday's performance at Austin Peay  
State University, which also sustained significant storm damage. 
University officials manned collection bins, where concertgoers 
contributed everything from loose change to $100 bills. 
</P>
<P>
	``God has blessed this town,'' said lead singer Mark Miller.  
``Sometimes he lets us know you can knock down buildings, but you 
can't kill the human spirit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller said the band was inspired to help after seeing accounts  
of the tornadoes. The damage was extensive but no one was killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Sawyer Brown's hits include ``Some Girls Do,'' ``All These  
Years'' and ``Thank God for You.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
