<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Owners: Expos To Stay in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JUPITER, Fla. (AP) -- The ownership group of the Montreal Expos  
remains optimistic it will be able to keep the team in Canada, its 
chairman said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	L. Jacques Menard said the partnership committee did not believe  
a March 6 deadline set by baseball was ``written in stone.'' That 
is the date that baseball declined to extend Friday for having a 
new ownership group and stadium financing in place in Montreal. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe baseball wants to keep a team in Montreal and will  
work with us as long as we continue to show progress,'' Menard 
said. ``The partners are committed to keeping the process going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Menard acknowledged two obstacles must be overcome.  
</P>
<P>
	He said a common ground must be reached with team president  
Claude Brochu, who has said he is willing to sell his 7.6 percent 
stake in the team but has rejected an offer of about $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as we are talking with Claude, we are making  
progress,'' Menard said. Brochu has previously been the primary 
point man for baseball, but the reorganized partnership does not 
include him. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, better economics could mean getting more support from both  
the provincial and federal government. Up to now, Quebec Premier 
Lucien Brouchard has publicly expressed strong opposition to public 
financing for a new stadium and there has been no mention of 
stadium financing in either the national or provincial budget. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have plans for a scaled-down stadium for about $75 million  
less than the $150 million we originally sought,'' Menard said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another member of the committee, Mark Routtenberg, said  
``baseball will address these problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If not, there are 15 or 16 other teams just like us. The other  
teams can not continue to subsidize us for up to 70 percent of our 
revenue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Expos, the only major league baseball team not to draw 1  
million fans in 1998, say they cannot survive at Olympic Stadium, 
which was built for the 1976 Summer Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, ownership groups in Washington, D.C., and northern  
Virginia are waiting to see what happens in Montreal. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the team is put up for sale with the blessing of major  
league baseball,'' says William Collins III, leader of the 
Virginia-based investor group, ``we stand ready to discuss the 
acquisition and relocation to the national capital area.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
