<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Saint Louis Coach May Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Saint Louis coach Charlie Spoonhour is expected  
to announce his resignation at the end of the latest in a series of 
frustrating seasons, according to reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Saint Louis is 14-15 heading into Wednesday's first-round game  
against Marquette in the Conference USA tournament. It's a big 
letdown from last season, when freshman guard Larry Hughes led the 
team to 22 victories and the NCAA tournament. Hughes left for the 
NBA after only one season and Spoonhour couldn't fill the huge gap. 
</P>
<P>
	Spoonhour produced consecutive NCAA appearances in 1994 and '95,  
both 23-win seasons, but followed up with disappointing records of 
16-14 and 11-18 before Hughes decided to stay home in part because 
of his ailing younger brother. Otherwise, Spoonhour has lost 
recruiting battles for the city's top talent. 
</P>
<P>
	In 16 Division I seasons, Spoonhour is 318-70. Before coming to  
Saint Louis, he produced five NCAA tournament teams in nine seasons 
at Southwest Missouri State. 
</P>
<P>
	Team spokesman Doug McIlhagga could not confirm reports that the  
school was ready to make a change after seven seasons under 
Spoonhour. 
</P>
<P>
	But rumors have circulated for months that Spoonhour, who has  
four years to go on a contract that pays him $325,000, has been 
talking about resigning or retiring. KSDK in St. Louis reported 
Sunday night that Spoonhour would quit after the Billikens' season 
ends, and that he would recommend longtime assistant Greg Lackey as 
his replacement. 
</P>
<P>
	Spoonhour downplayed the talk after a victory in mid-January in  
an interview with the Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every time we lose, I think about it,'' Spoonhour said. ``Then  
we win and I think I could coach forever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also said then that nothing would be decided until the season  
is over. 
</P>
<P>
	Spoonhour made no mention of his future at the team's annual  
awards banquet Sunday night at a local hotel, but later said 
``Anybody can hang on and keep making money. I don't want to do 
that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
