<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- A real estate magnate whose  
apartment building collapsed and killed eight people last year may 
lose his U.S. assets if a Rio judge has his way. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Joao Baptista Chagas Filho requested Friday that U.S.  
justice officials freeze the U.S. assets of Sergio Naya, a 
developer and former federal legislator. If accepted by U.S. 
courts, the legal action would stop Naya from selling two hot-pink 
$45 million twin towers he is finishing in Orlando, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Naya became widely despised after a 22-story Rio apartment  
building his construction company erected caved in last year. 
</P>
<P>
	City inspectors later found the firm had laced cement with beach  
sand and seashells, leaving pillars inadequately reinforced. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Eduardo Lutz, attorney for the Palace II Residents  
Association, Naya eventually will have to pay as much as $165 
million to satisfy the claims of the building's 130 families, who 
were left homeless after the collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's ruling is meant to guarantee part of that payment.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Police have unearthed the remains of an  
American couple missing for two years in southern Chile, and the 
couple's son, a former U.S. marine, is being held as a suspect in 
their deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Maria Ines Sciolla in Chillan told TV Channel 13,  
broadcast in the Chilean capital of Santiago, that the two bodies 
had been identified as Richard Bristow and Patsy Thurman, both 65. 
</P>
<P>
	Their remains were found Saturday in the backyard of the house  
where their son, identified as Marion Lee Bristow, 40, had been 
living until last year in Chillan, 255 miles south of Santiago. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge said the son will undergo psychiatric tests. He has  
not been charged. 
</P>
<P>
	The government newspaper La Nacion reported, however, that the  
former marine confessed the killings in Temuco, 400 miles south of 
Santiago, where he was arrested two days ago. 
</P>
<P>
	He is expected to be taken back to Chillan next week and brought  
before a judge there. The victims are believed to come from the 
Houston area, according to press reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
