<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Feb. 28, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Israeli Troop Convoy Bombed, 3 Die  
</P>
<P>
	MARJAYOUN, Lebanon (AP) -- Lebanese guerrillas detonated a  
roadside bomb near a convoy carrying senior Israeli officers 
Sunday, killing at least three and wounding several others, 
Lebanese security officials said. The Iranian-backed Hezbollah 
guerrilla group claimed responsibility for the attack in southern 
Lebanon shortly before midday. There was no immediate confirmation 
from Israel of the attack or the casualties.It was the second 
serious blow to Israel's army in southern Lebanon in less than a 
week. 

</P>
<P>
	Deputy Malaysian P.M. Was Beaten  
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- Malaysia's former police chief  
admitted to beating ousted deputy prime minister Anwar Ibrahim in a 
police lock up last year. The admission came yesterday from the 
officer's lawyer before a panel probing the assault. The news is 
likely to further discredit the Malaysian police, which has been 
condemned by human rights groups, for allegedly using harsh 
methods. The panel is investigating the beating separately from the 
trial of Anwar, who was removed from his post and charged with 
illegal sexual acts and corruption in September. Anwar insists the 
charges were trumped up to eliminate him as a rival to Prime 
Minister Mahathir Mohamad. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-General Leads Nigeria Elections  
</P>
<P>
	ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- Early poll results this morning gave  
retired Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo the lead in two states and the 
capital in Nigeria's presidential elections. Marking the final 
phase of democracy's return to Africa's most populous nation, tens 
of millions of Nigerians turned out at polls yesterday in the 
long-awaited election. Many hope the event will sweep aside 15 
years of corrupt and brutal military rule. The race pits Obasanjo, 
a former military ruler seeking a civilian comeback 20 years after 
leaving power, against former finance minister Olu Falae. 

</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin May Stay in Hospital 1 Week  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- President Boris Yeltsin was in stable condition  
today after bleeding of his ulcer was stopped, but he could remain 
in the hospital for up to a week, news reports said. Yeltsin was 
readmitted to the Central Clinical Hospital yesterday and was 
``undergoing a prescribed course of treatment'' for the bleeding 
ulcer, the Interfax news agency said. Doctors ordered Yeltsin to 
limit his workload and meetings as much as possible over the next 
few days to ensure a complete recovery, the report said. 

</P>
<P>
	Clintons Relax in Utah's Mountains  
</P>
<P>
	PARK CITY, Utah (AP) -- President Clinton is nestled among snowy  
mountains on vacation, but he doesn't plan to do any skiing. He and 
his family are in Utah for a reunion to celebrate daughter 
Chelsea's 19th birthday. Governor Mike Leavitt says Clinton has 
skied only once before, and doesn't plan a second outing. Instead, 
he plans to read. The Clintons are borrowing the mountaintop home 
of Hollywood executive Jeffrey Katzenberg. 

</P>
<P>
	Ethiopia Claims 'Victory' in War  
</P>
<P>
	ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) -- Ethiopia declared ``total victory''  
in its war with Eritrea today, a day after its rival in the Horn of 
Africa accepted an African-sponsored proposal to end their border 
dispute. Diplomats at the United Nations said Eritrea's unexpected 
acceptance of the Organization of African Unity peace plan came 
after it suffered a battlefield reversal when Ethiopian troops 
punched through a key front line at Badme this week. The Horn of 
Africa neighbors are contesting parts of their barren, largely 
uninhabited 620-mile border. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan To Conduct Heart Transplant  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A team of doctors assembled today for Japan's first  
heart transplant in more than three decades after a hospital 
declared a comatose woman brain-dead. The 44-year-old woman's heart 
and lungs will be sent by helicopter to a university hospital in 
Osaka, where a patient is waiting to receive the organs. Another 
patient was to receive the woman's liver. The woman is the first 
person carrying a valid donor's card to be declared brain-dead 
since a new law in 1997 allowed doctors to make the diagnosis. 

</P>
<P>
	Bulls Beat Hornets 94-77  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Winless at home since last year's NBA Finals and  
fresh from their worst loss yet, the Chicago Bulls got exactly what 
they needed: A visit from a team even worse off than they are. Toni 
Kukoc led four Bulls in double figures with 16 points yesterday as 
the Bulls coasted to a 94-77 victory over the Charlotte Hornets. 

</P>
<P>
	Venus, Coetzer Advance to Finals  
</P>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Top-seeded defending champion Venus  
Williams moved into the final of the IGA SuperThrift Tennis Classic 
by beating qualifier Lilia Osterloh 6-2, 6-3 last night. Williams, 
ranked No. 5 in the world, needed 61 minutes to advance opposite 
No. 3 Amanda Coetzer, who beat flu-ridden Anna Kournikova 6-4, 6-2 
in the other semifinal. 


</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
