<HEADLINE> Norway Wins Women's Biathlon Relay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE PLACID, N.Y. (AP) -- Norway's powerful foursome captured  
first place in the women's relay competition and Russia took first 
place in the men's relay during the World Cup Biathlon competition 
Sunday at Lake Placid. 
</P>
<P>
	Norway finished first with a total time of 1:33.05 in the  
women's competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Ukraine was second in 1:58.6 while Finland took home the bronze  
with a finishing time of 3:21.1. 
</P>
<P>
	The American team of Kristina Sabasteanski, Kara Salmela, Jill  
Troutner and Rachel Steer finished eighth. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia had a total time of 1:20.46 in the men's competition.  
</P>
<P>
	Germany won the silver, finishing 49.2 seconds behind Russia,  
and Norway won the bronze while finishing at 2:03.5. 
</P>
<P>
	The American team of Jay Hakkinen, Richard Oliver, Jeremy Teela  
and David Gieck finished in 12th place, at 7:23.9. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990228.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 14:24:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Members Defend Themselves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- With Juan Antonio Samaranch calling  
criticism of the Olympic scandal ``exaggerated,'' implicated IOC 
members defended themselves Sunday at the organization's 
headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate word on the fate of 13 members embroiled  
in the worst ethics scandal in the history of the International 
Olympic Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC vice president Richard Pound, head of the six-man inquiry  
panel, said his group had not finished its work concerning the Salt 
Lake City report that found more than $1.2 million in bribes were 
made to one-fifth of the IOC membership. 
</P>
<P>
	Pound expects to report his findings to the IOC executive board  
next week. He is under pressure to wrap up his report before the 
IOC general assembly meets March 17-18 to address the scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to stop the bleeding by March 17,'' he said. ``Death  
by 1,000 cuts isn't much fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch, in Spanish newspapers this weekend, played down many  
of the accusations in the Salt Lake report and said the bidders for 
Olympic sites must share the blame. 
</P>
<P>
	``The criticism has been exaggerated and it has done  
disproportionate damage,'' the IOC president told the newspaper El 
Periodico. 
</P>
<P>
	At least three members implicated in the scandal -- Phil Coles of  
Australia, Ashwini Kumar of India and Agustin Arroyo of Ecuador -- 
traveled to Lausanne to give evidence to Pound. Tight security 
prevented checks to see if others were present. 
</P>
<P>
	``I came here because I wanted to explain I didn't do  
anything,'' Kumar said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine members resigned or were suspended last month in the first  
round of Pound's investigations. The weekend meeting focused on 
three that remained under investigation and 10 new names that 
appeared in the Salt Lake report. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of the 10 cases reported later, only one or two could have  
committed irregularities,'' Samaranch told the Union of Catalan 
Sports Federations in Barcelona on Friday on the eve of the 
meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the Barcelona newspaper La Vanguardia, Samaranch  
said only one case might merit consideration and the other nine 
were without foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	The 78-year-old Spaniard also placed blame on the bidders.  
</P>
<P>
	``They (IOC members) are guilty 50 percent, the other 50 percent  
is the responsibility of the bidding cities, which are more 
aggressive every day,'' Samaranch said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pound's panel can recommend that those found guilty of  
wrongdoing be expelled or sanctioned. The final decision will be 
made at next month's general assembly, which will vote on 
expulsions and sweeping reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	The most prominent case is that of Kim Un-yong, the executive  
board member from South Korea and president of the confederation of 
Olympic sports bodies. He is accused of using his influence to get 
lucrative jobs in television and entertainment for his children. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles, one of the most influential sports officials in the 2000  
Sydney Olympics, was with the panel for about one hour and declined 
comment afterward. 
</P>
<P>
	He has denied that Salt Lake boosters paid for lavish travel and  
vacations and has threatened legal action to clear his name. 
</P>
<P>
	Kumar is accused of being given a plane ticket for the IOC  
meeting in Hungary. That session awarded the 2002 Winter Games to 
Salt Lake. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't receive any ticket,'' Kumar said. He said while the  
ticket receipt bore the name Kumar, the first name was different. 
</P>
<P>
	Arroyo, one of the members suspended last month, said he went  
before the panel because he was ``not at all satisfied'' with the 
initial inquiry findings. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a lot of wrong information from Salt Lake City. I  
don't like to use the word lie ... I just say it's not true,'' the 
75-year-old IOC veteran said. 
</P>
<P>
	``In my opinion, I haven't done anything wrong,'' said Arroyo,  
wearing the IOC trademark tie pin of five rings. 
</P>
<P>
	The inquiry commission in January accused Arroyo of accepting  
payments from Salt Lake bidders for himself and a family member 
that amounted to $19,000, in addition to generous travel expenses 
for visits. 
</P>
<P>
	The full IOC session in March will decide whether to implement  
the executive board's orders that he should be expelled after more 
than 30 years as a member. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel also was expected to examine files from about a dozen  
cities that bid for the Olympics between 1996 and 2004. The IOC had 
asked the cities to detail any wrongdoing by members during their 
bids. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
