<DOCNO> APW19990228.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 08:05:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Deformed Hand Clue in 1972 Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Detective John Krol and his partner were armed  
with only a sketch and a key clue: The man wanted for a 1972 murder 
on a Brooklyn street had a deformed left hand. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the end, that was enough.  
</P>
<P>
	After receiving an anonymous phone tip that Joseph Carfagno was  
spotted on West 49th Street, in the midst of Manhattan's bustling 
Broadway theater district, Krol drove in from Brooklyn Friday to 
ask around. And then he spotted him standing in front of a garage, 
looking at age 71 just like the police artist projected he would. 
</P>
<P>
	``I asked for his ID, and he tried to give it to me with his  
right hand,'' Krol said. ``I said, 'No, I want you to show me your 
ID with your left hand.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Out came the stumpy, web-like fingers Carfagno was born with.  
</P>
<P>
	``We had him,'' Krol said. ``This was the most serious, oldest  
unsolved case we had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police have been looking for Carfagno since 1972, when they  
believe he opened fire during a fight outside a bar, killing 
35-year-old Joseph Destafano. 
</P>
<P>
	The case had become a focus in recent years for Krol after he  
was diagnosed with Lyme disease and began periodically coming off 
street patrol to work investigations. He would get reports now and 
then that someone spotted Carfagno, who worked as a bookie and used 
the alias Carl Decarlo. The last report was in the 1980s -- on the 
same block. 
</P>
<P>
	``He looks like a nice old Italian gentleman, like anybody else  
out there on the street, with gray hair, balding,'' Krol said of 
Carfagno, who was convicted of rape in 1952 and was found guilty of 
possession of gambling materials in 1967. ``He seems pleasant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And on Saturday night, the elderly man was awaiting arraignment  
on murder charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1972 victim was shot to death after arguing with Carfagno in  
the same Brooklyn bar later used in the Mafia movie, ``Donnie 
Brasco,'' starring Al Pacino as a Mob hit man. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
