<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Feb. 28, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	US Won't Link China Rights, WTO Bid  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- The Clinton administration will not link progress  
on human rights to China's efforts to join the World Trade 
Organization, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said Monday. 
``We determined some time ago that it was not a good idea to link 
human rights and trade and that we actually make better progress 
with both when they are not linked,'' Albright said at a joint news 
conference with Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan. 

</P>
<P>
	4 Israelis Die in Lebanon Bombing  
</P>
<P>
	MARJAYOUN, Lebanon (AP) -- Lebanese guerillas detonated two bombs  
beside a military convoy Sunday, killing a brigadier general and 
three other Israelis in one of the most serious attacks on Israel's 
forces in southern Lebanon. Hezbollah, an Iranian-backed Lebanese 
guerrilla group, claimed responsibility for the attack. Brig. Gen. 
Erez Gerstein was the highest-ranking officer to die in Lebanon 
since the 1982 Israeli invasion. Two Israeli sergeants and an 
Israel Radio reporter, all of whom were in Gerstein's vehicle, also 
were killed. 

</P>
<P>
	Bombings Rock Zambian Capital  
</P>
<P>
	LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) -- A bomb exploded Sunday at the Angolan  
Embassy and four other area's in Zambia's capital. One security 
official at the embassy was killed and another was slightly 
wounded, state TV reported. Witnesses said police defused a second 
device at the embassy. There was no immediate claim of 
responsibility. President Frederick Chiluba condemned the bombings 
as ``unacceptable acts of terrorism'' and asked Zambians to be on 
the alert for further attacks. Relations between Zambia and 
neighboring Angola have been strained over allegations Zambia 
allowed illegal weapon shipments to pass through its territory to 
Angolan rebels. Zambia denies the allegations. 

</P>
<P>
	Obasanjo Leads Nigeria Election  
</P>
<P>
	ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- Retired Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo appears  
increasingly certain to win Nigeria's presidential vote. Election 
officials said Obasanjo had captured 62 percent of the vote with 31 
of Nigeria's 36 states and the federal capital reporting. Final 
results were not expected until Monday. Obasanjo's opponent, Olu 
Falae, the former finance minister, plans to contest the results. 
International observers reported ballot box-stuffing and other 
serious voting irregularities. 

</P>
<P>
	Gov. Fires Head of NJ State Police  
</P>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Gov. Christie Whitman fired the head of the  
New Jersey State Police Sunday after he said in a newspaper 
interview that minority groups were more likely to be involved in 
drug trafficking. Police Superintendent Col. Carl Williams also has 
come under fire over allegations that the agency practices racial 
profiling. Whitman said the state's law enforcement system must be 
free of bias. 

</P>
<P>
	Americans Kidnapped in Colombia  
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Three Americans were kidnapped by  
suspected leftist rebels in northeastern Colombia after researching 
an indigenous group on its reservation, authorities said Sunday. 
They were seized Thursday near the Venezuelan border while on their 
way home from studying the U'wa culture. No group claimed 
responsibility, but several leftist rebel bands operate in the 
area, said Colombia's anti-kidnapping chief. 

</P>
<P>
	Orthodox Jews Protest Court Rulings  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- About 25,000 Orthodox Jews prayed in the pouring  
rain Sunday to protest recent Israeli supreme court rulings that 
could reduce Orthodox influence over everyday activities in the 
Jewish state. Two weeks ago, 200,000 Orthodox Jews protested in 
Jerusalem over the same grievances -- among them a recent Israeli 
supreme court edict that could allow seminary students to be 
drafted, and another challenging Orthodox control of marriage, 
burial and Sabbath travel. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Inch Higher  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stock prices inched higher Monday. The  
Nikkei Stock Average rose 36.51 points to 14,404.05 in the first 30 
minutes of trading. 

</P>
<P>
	Suns Defeat Warriors 102-89  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Cliff Robinson scored 20 points and the Phoenix  
Suns held the Golden State Warriors to an NBA record-tying six 
points in the fourth quarter of a 102-89 victory Sunday night. 
After trailing by 15 with 5 1/2 minutes left in the third quarter and 
by seven entering the fourth, the Suns held Golden State to the 
lowest-scoring quarter in team history. It also was the fewest 
points ever allowed by the Suns in one period. 

</P>
<P>
	Lakers Beat Rockets 106-90  
</P>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Dennis Rodman and Rick Fox helped lead  
the Los Angeles Lakers to a 106-90 victory over the Houston Rockets 
Sunday night. Rodman, playing 26 minutes, had two points, 10 
rebounds and two assists as Los Angeles raised its record to 2-0 
since Kurt Rambis became coach. Fox scored 15 of his 21 points in 
the beginning of the fourth quarter. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by STEPHANIE GASKELL  
</P>
