<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Feb. 28, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Japan Conducts Heart Transplant  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese doctors today completed a heart  
transplant, the first such operation in this country in three 
decades and also the first under a new law recognizing brain death. 
The donor, a 44-year-old woman, was the first person to be declared 
brain dead since a controversial law was passed in 1997 to allow 
doctors to make the diagnosis. Before the law, Japan had not 
allowed a person to be declared dead until the heart had stopped, 
making it almost impossible to transplant some organs because they 
deteriorate too rapidly once the heart ceases. The recipient is a 
man in his 40s. Japan's only other heart transplant was in 1968. It 
prompted criminal investigations, although the surgeon was never 
indicted. 

</P>
<P>
	Search for Missing Boy Resumes  
</P>
<P>
	NORTON, Mass. (AP) -- People searching for a missing 9-year-old  
boy are still hopeful of finding him alive, but acknowledge that 
time isn't on their side. Corey Anderson disappeared Thursday after 
he went out into a driving snowstorm to look for his missing dog. 
The dog returned an hour later. More than 200 people covered an 
area with a one and a-half mile radius last night. A helicopter 
with heat-seeking equipment also joined in the search. 

</P>
<P>
	Iraqi Sites Attacked by US Fighters  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. Air Force F-15 fighters attacked Iraqi  
military installations today with bombs and missiles after planes 
patrolling the northern no-fly zone came under anti-aircraft fire, 
U.S. military officials said. The planes fired three air-to-ground 
missiles and dropped eight bombs on targets mostly around the city 
of Mosul, about 250 miles north of Baghdad, a military spokesman 
said. Allied warplanes have prohibited Iraqi military flights over 
northern and southern Iraq since shortly after the 1991 Gulf War to 
protect Kurdish rebel and Shiite Muslim groups. 

</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin May Stay in Hospital a Week  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Doctors say ailing Russian President Boris Yeltsin  
is in stable condition today after the bleeding of his ulcer was 
stopped, but he could remain in the hospital for up to a week. The 
68-year-old was readmitted yesterday after it was found that he 
needed more treatment for an ulcer for which he was hospitalized 
for two weeks last month. Yeltsin has had a slew of illnesses in 
recent months and has spent weeks away from his Kremlin office, 
raising doubts about his ability to complete his term, which ends 
next year. 

</P>
<P>
	Tensions Increase in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The disappearance of two Serb  
civilians has tensions soaring in Kosovo. International peace 
monitors believe the two were abducted by ethnic Albanian rebels. 
The suspected kidnapping has touched off angry protests by Serbs in 
the area. Some 40 Serbs surrounded a police station but later 
dispersed after police and monitors assured them they would try to 
secure the civilians' release. Forty Serbs disappeared last summer 
in the territory controlled by the rebel Kosovo Liberation army and 
are presumed dead. 

</P>
<P>
	Four Killed in Bombing in Lebanon  
</P>
<P>
	MARJAYOUN, Lebanon (AP) -- Lebanese guerrillas detonated two  
bombs near an Israeli convoy today, killing four people, Lebanese 
officials said. A general was reported among the dead, the 
highest-ranking officer killed in Lebanon in more than 16 years. 
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah group claimed responsibility for the 
twin bombings. Israel has occupied the zone in southern Lebanon 
since 1985 in a bid to protect its northern territory from 
cross-border attacks. Hezbollah is the most active of guerrilla 
groups fighting to oust the Israelis and their militia allies. 

</P>
<P>
	Webb Sets Record in Aussie Masters  
</P>
<P>
	GOLD COAST, Australia (AP) -- Karrie Webb set a record in women's  
golf today when she won the Australian Ladies Masters in 26-under 
par, finishing 10 strokes ahead of her nearest rival. The 
Australian star closed with a 68 after previous rounds of 63-67-64 
for a 262 total. She broke the LPGA record of 23-under held by 
South Korea's Se Ri Pak (1998) and Americans Wendy Ward (1997) and 
Lisa Walters (1998). The PGA Tour record is 28-under by John 
Houston in last year's Hawaiian Open. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
</P>
</TEXT>
