<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.J. Foes May Clash in Senate Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- They are the Celtics and Lakers of New Jersey  
politics. Rome and Carthage. Mr. Hatfield and Ms. McCoy. 
</P>
<P>
	Their political conflicts defined the 1990s in New Jersey and  
influenced national conventional wisdom about taxes, campaign 
promises and the public's appetite for bad news. 
</P>
<P>
	Now fate and term limits may conspire to pit Republican  
Christine Whitman against Democrat Jim Florio yet again. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman, the current governor, and former governor Florio are  
considering a run for the Senate seat being vacated by Democrat 
Frank Lautenberg in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Other aspiring politicians in both parties will surely have a  
say in the matter. Still, if destiny has a vote, it will surely 
choose to end the decade with an encore performance of the Battle 
of the '90s: 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman, who cut taxes, against Florio, who raised them.  
</P>
<P>
	Whitman, a child of privilege with a common touch, against  
Florio, a child of hardship but distant from the public. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman, who waited until the last year of her first term to  
tackle sky-high auto insurance rates, against Florio, who began 
implementing his own ideas on insurance overhaul virtually the 
instant he took office. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't often get to read the next chapter in a lot of good  
fiction, and we don't often get to read the next chapter in 
politics. But here it comes,'' said Ingrid Reed, who monitors New 
Jersey campaigns for the Eagleton Institute of Politics at Rutgers 
University. 
</P>
<P>
	Florio, out of politics since Whitman defeated him in 1993, said  
he has a new perspective and new ideas after five years in the 
private sector. 
</P>
<P>
	He said a campaign against Whitman would pit ``clashing  
philosophies about what government can do and shouldn't do, how you 
can finance it, whether you think short-term or long-term.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's almost a classic case study of what an election should be  
about,'' Florio said. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman, facing a mandatory career change in 2001 after serving  
the maximum two terms as governor, might welcome a rematch. 
</P>
<P>
	Running as a virtual unknown against Sen. Bill Bradley in 1990,  
Whitman cornered Bradley into refusing to state an opinion on the a 
$2.8 billion tax increase implemented that year by Florio. Whitman 
almost rode the issue to an upset of Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, she ran against Florio for governor and won.  
</P>
<P>
	Florio considered seeking a rematch in 1997 but deferred. Still,  
Whitman used Florio's tax increase against Democratic challenger 
Jim McGreevey, who voted for the Florio plan while in the state 
legislature. 
</P>
<P>
	By choosing governors in odd-numbered years, New Jersey often  
sends signals to the nation about the public mood. 
</P>
<P>
	Florio's victory in the 1989 governor's race supposedly sent  
word that America was ready to roll up its sleeves in the 1990s and 
address debts and inequalities left from the boom years of Ronald 
Reagan and New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean. 
</P>
<P>
	But Florio's unpopular efforts to close a budget deficit and  
increase funding to poor urban schools opened the door for Whitman. 
Her victory in 1993 provided a blueprint for Republican 
gubernatorial candidates elsewhere: promise income tax cuts, then 
provide them fast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
