<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Fanfare for Orioles' Baines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- If he wanted to, Harold Baines  
could talk for hours about the impressive numbers he's amassed 
during an outstanding 19-year career in the major leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	If he wanted to, Baines could have broken into a haughty jog  
after each of his 348 career homers or enjoyed the notoriety 
deserving of a player who has hit .300 seven times and played in 
five All-Star games. 
</P>
<P>
	Baines, however, prefers to operate silently and without  
fanfare. The Baltimore Orioles' designated hitter doesn't 
particularly care to talk about himself and probably considers a 
broad smile to be an overt show of emotion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't need the magazine covers or the newspaper coverage to  
be happy,'' Baines said Sunday. ``I'm not afraid to talk to people, 
but I don't need it. Some players like talking after games; that's 
their personality. That's not me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His creed is simple: Go to the plate, take your cuts and act  
like a professional. 
</P>
<P>
	``When they announce his name, he's already gone to the plate,''  
Orioles manager Ray Miller said. ``When he hits a home run he runs 
around the bases and sits down. If he gets a game-winning hit, 
he'll just walk off the field and shake hands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	B.J. Surhoff is one of the quietest players on the team, but  
he's downright chatty compared to the soft-spoken Baines, his 
neighbor in the Baltimore clubhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	``Harold doesn't say a whole lot, but when he does say something  
it makes a lot of sense,'' Surhoff said. ``He holds his emotions 
inside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's not as if Baines doesn't have anything to talk about. The  
left-handed hitter has more RBIs than any designated hitter in 
major-league history (837) and ranks second among DHs in homers and 
hits. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, at age 39, he hit .300 with nine homers and 57 RBIs.  
His .347 batting average with men on base ranked third in the AL. 
</P>
<P>
	Baines can even be used as a weapon when he's not in the  
starting lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	``You want him in there because he has such good numbers, but  
he's the one guy I have that every time he gets up in the dugout, 
you see the other team get a lefty up,'' Miller said. ``Sometimes I 
call him over just to talk, and while he's walking across the 
dugout the other manager is already on the phone to his bullpen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Were it not for the DH rule, Baines would have retired a decade  
ago because of numerous operations on both his damaged knees. There 
were times last season that Miller considered using pitcher Mike 
Mussina in the outfield before Baines, who was hobbled for weeks 
with a strained hamstring and hasn't played defense for years. 
</P>
<P>
	``The 10 years I did play outfield, I loved it because you could  
help the team one night with hitting and the next night with 
defense,'' Baines said. 
</P>
<P>
	His lone contribution these days is with his bat. Oh, but what a  
lethal bat it is, in part because Baines can focus fully on the 
offensive aspect of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It helps if you know the only job you have to worry about it  
hitting,'' he said. ``The only thing I have to be concerned about 
is what kind of pitches the other guy throws. And if I make an out, 
I can go back and study what I did wrong instead of changing gears 
and playing defense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although he turns 40 later this month, Baines said he won't  
think about quitting the game until he sees what type of numbers he 
puts up this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``People ask me when I'm going to retire, I say my performance  
will tell me that,'' he said. ``If you can help the team, they'll 
still want you. Once it's gone, all you can do is look back, so I 
want to stay on this ride as long as I can.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
