<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Quake Survivors Arrive in N.Y. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- They lost their mother in the earthquake in  
Colombia. On Sunday -- with tearful hugs -- the Amaya girls were 
reunited with their father in Queens. 
</P>
<P>
	Jenny Amaya, 12, who lost her right leg below the knee in the  
Jan. 25 earthquake, is believed to be the only U.S. citizen hurt in 
the disaster that killed more than 1,170 people. 
</P>
<P>
	She and her sister, Maritza, 13, landed at LaGuardia Airport  
Sunday and saw their father, Emilio Amaya, for the first time in 
more than five years. Two local members of Congress accompanied the 
girls. 
</P>
<P>
	Jenny was surrounded by stuffed animals as she left the airplane  
in a wheelchair. She and her sister cried as their father gave them 
an emotional embrace. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thank God for bringing my family here,'' Amaya said in  
Spanish. 
</P>
<P>
	Amaya, a textile factory worker in Queens, came to the United  
States in 1985 but sent his wife and children back to their 
hometown of Pereira in Colombia six years ago. Jenny was born in 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to hug and kiss them and tell them that I really love  
them,'' Amaya said through an interpreter just before the girls 
arrived. He brought two warm winter coats to the airport for them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jenny's birthday was last week, so we plan to celebrate,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The girls, who appeared frightened by a crowd of reporters,  
photographers and television crews, did not speak. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Rep. Nydia Velazquez, D-Brooklyn, who traveled with the  
children, said they were anxious to see their father. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we were about to land the girls were saying 'We are going  
to see daddy, we are going to see daddy,''' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jenny and Maritza's mother, Luz Dary, was at a bank cashing a  
check from Amaya when she died. The earthquake sent a wall tumbling 
on top of her and Jenny. Maritza was not injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Velazquez and U.S. Rep. Joseph Crowley, D-Queens, heard the  
family's story and went to Colombia to bring the girls to New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Jenny and Maritza have lived with their grandparents in Pereira  
since the earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
	Amaya had been sending money to support the family. He was  
devastated by the news of his wife's death, but was unable to fly 
back to get the girls because he is an undocumented immigrant who 
would likely have trouble reentering the United States if he 
leaves. 
</P>
<P>
	Jenny will receive medical treatment -- including a prosthesis  
for her damaged leg -- at Elmhurst and Mount Sinai Hospitals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
