<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Century-Old Mill's Future Unknown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILLINOCKET, Maine (AP) -- After Eldon Gagnier went to work for  
Great Northern Paper in 1947, the company loaned equipment to help 
him pour a foundation for his new house. 
</P>
<P>
	Then it sent a carpenter to help him build it.  
</P>
<P>
	The company did the same for countless other employees. It also  
built playgrounds, a ballpark and a golf course, and paid most of 
the local taxes. Best of all, it paid its workers well, and in 
return earned their loyalty. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the best company to work for,'' said Hubert Voisine, 70,  
who was given a free plot on paper company land for his cottage 
after he retired. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, with the century-old mill's future unknown, it's time for  
employees to pitch in. And they will do it in grand fashion if they 
pull off what they believe would be the first employee takeover of 
an American paper mill. 
</P>
<P>
	``At first, I was a little pessimistic,'' said Alan ``Butch''  
Higgins, president of one of nine unions involved in the buyout 
plan. But now, ``I think it's going to happen, and real fast, 
too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For generations, Millinocket was an island of prosperity in the  
middle of Maine's vast industrial forest. It seemed everybody had a 
shiny car or pickup, a snowmobile or two, a decent house and a good 
job. 
</P>
<P>
	``The mill was the backbone of the town and the only industry in  
town,'' said Francis Larkin, 77, a 31-year veteran employee. 
``Pretty near everything in the community they've done something 
for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But times have changed.  
</P>
<P>
	Bowater Inc., Great Northern's parent company and the nation's  
largest newsprint maker, announced a year ago that it will sell the 
mill instead of investing in upgrades. 
</P>
<P>
	Changes around town reflect concerns about the future of the  
Millinocket mill, the economic engine for the town of 6,500. 
</P>
<P>
	Storefront after storefront have ``For Rent'' signs. ``For  
Sale'' signs are sprouting on the lawns of many of the town's 
vinyl-sided homes, and a couple of the schools have closed. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can get a good house for $50,000,'' said Voisine, relaxing  
with his pals at the retirees' club. ``I know a lot of houses, they 
were asking $80,000 and they got $40,000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the search for a buyer of the mill turned up no takers,  
the unions proposed a takeover in which the workers would buy 30 
percent of the stock, management would buy 10 percent and other 
investors would buy the remainder. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think people are finally getting a little bit of optimism,''  
said Higgins, the mill's payroll coordinator. 
</P>
<P>
	Hope is mixed with skepticism among some of the mill's remaining  
900 workers, down from around 1,400 at one time. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Gagnon, a salaried employee, and union paperworker Jim  
Burgess fear that Bowater will sell the mill without its 
power-generating system included in the deal. The combination of 
papermaking and power-generation, said Gagnon, makes the 
Millinocket mill unique. 
</P>
<P>
	Already, Bowater has sold off 1.6 million acres of its  
timberlands. And while the Columbia, S.C.-based company plans to 
invest $200 million in its other Maine mill a few miles down the 
road in East Millinocket, the older mill that is valued at $125 
million by the town continues to languish. 
</P>
<P>
	``What they've done is taken a perfect diamond, and broken it  
off a piece at a time,'' said Gagnon, sitting with Burgess in the 
Appalachian Trail Cafe on a clear February afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Burgess said he's confident the buyout will happen, but Gagnon  
said many mill workers have their doubts. He said workers have been 
through so many ups and downs that they've become immune to the 
stress. 
</P>
<P>
	If the unions that represent 640 employees do not succeed in  
their buyout, there may be another option for the town: profit from 
its beauty. 
</P>
<P>
	Millinocket is the principal gateway to Baxter State Park, a  
204,733-acre wilderness preserve that draws thousands of campers, 
mountain climbers, hikers and nature lovers. 
</P>
<P>
	It also leads to one of the nation's top whitewater rivers, the  
West Branch of the Penobscot, not to mention scores of lakes and 
ponds that are prized by anglers and boaters, and an endless 
network of snowmobile trails. 
</P>
<P>
	Local folks don't seem overly enthused about promoting the  
wonderland that is their backyard to the rest of the world. Some 
fret that too many outsiders pass through already without stopping. 
</P>
<P>
	But nobody is saying Millinocket will curl up and die, even if  
the buyout fails. 
</P>
<P>
	``Change is hard to come by, but they can deal with it,'' said  
state Rep. Joseph Clark, D-Millinocket. ``Millinocket is a town 
that can survive almost anything.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
