<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Linux Nips at Dominant Microsoft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	It hardly seems like a group intent on remaking the universe:  
8,000 technology experts devoted to a software for running 
computers called Linux that most non-technical types haven't even 
heard of. 
</P>
<P>
	But when they meet Tuesday for Linux World in San Jose, Calif.,  
these computer buyers and enthusiasts will talk like passionate 
rebels of how Linux may one day be a viable alternative to the 
overwhelmingly dominant Windows software from Microsoft Corp. 
They'll underscore how Linux is breaking free of its grassroots 
beginnings and edging into the mainstream. 
</P>
<P>
	``Linux has become the poster child for anyone feeling any  
animosity for Microsoft,'' said Charlie Greco, chief executive of 
IDG World Expo, which is sponsoring its first-ever Linux event in 
response to surging interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Developed in the early 1990s by a Finnish student named Linus  
Torvalds, Linux (pronounced LINN-nucks) is a version of the Unix 
operating system used by businesses to run computer networks and 
Internet sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike most software writers, Torvalds released the basic  
blueprints for his system on the Internet and today Linux can be 
downloaded for free off the Web, or bought at retail stores for as 
little as $30. 
</P>
<P>
	Its popularity is growing fast as users embrace Linux's  
flexibility and its ability to avoid crashing. Demand is growing 
even though the software usually requires users to memorize and 
type in commands, similar to the DOS software that preceded 
Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	One advantage for Linux -- it's constantly being updated.  
</P>
<P>
	An army of volunteer developers scattered around the world works  
with Torvalds -- who now lives in Santa Clara, Calif. -- to improve 
it and make it easier to use. 
</P>
<P>
	For instance, some are working on sprucing up a Windows-style  
``point and click'' graphical interface for Linux. 
</P>
<P>
	To be sure, it's far too early to tell if the high-tech reality  
lives up to the excitement. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft officials portray Linux as nothing more than a minor  
rival. Windows runs about 85 percent of the world's personal 
computers, and Microsoft is notoriously aggressive in beating back 
threats to its software dominance. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials contend that because Linux developers are so  
scattered, chaos will deter Linux from ever catching on in a big 
way. 
</P>
<P>
	``Linux is a hype-rich topic at the moment in the marketplace,''  
said Ed Muth, Microsoft's group product manager for Windows NT. 
</P>
<P>
	``The great majority of our customers are not considering  
Linux,'' Muth said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, some big names are endorsing Linux. Intel Corp., the  
world's largest maker of chips for personal computers, could 
announce as early as this week a multimillion dollar investment in 
VA Research, a Mountain View, Calif., maker of computers pre-loaded 
with Linux. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel and VA officials declined comment last week, but industry  
sources say VA's machines will be adapted to work with Intel's 
upcoming chip for high-end business computers, known as Merced. 
</P>
<P>
	Last fall Intel took a stake in Red Hat, a Durham, N.C.-based  
distributor of Linux software. Several major computer makers such 
as Hewlett Packard Co. and IBM Corp. have begun selling machines 
loaded with Linux. 
</P>
<P>
	Shipments of Linux software jumped 48 percent to 2.9 million  
last year, says International Data Corp., a research firm owned by 
IDG World Expo's parent. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Linux's use in business computers is a tiny fraction of  
more established Unix systems and Windows NT, and the software 
rarely appears on desktop computers. 
</P>
<P>
	One reason is there are relatively few software applications --  
such as word processors or spreadsheets -- written to work with 
Linux. 
</P>
<P>
	While Microsoft has no current plans to write such programs,  
others are. This could help Linux make inroads into desktops, said 
William Peterson, an analyst with International Data. 
</P>
<P>
	``IDC firmly believes this will be the year for Linux  
software,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	To be sure, this isn't the first time rival technologies have  
tried to usurp the Microsoft crown. Other challengers such as 
ultra-simple computers tied to networks, the Java programming 
language by Sun Microsystems Inc., and even the Internet itself 
were pitched as Microsoft killers -- only to be beaten back by the 
company's counterattacks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone is talking about Linux emerging as a powerful system,  
but not many people are talking about the Microsoft factor,'' said 
Ullas Naik, an analyst with First Albany Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, Microsoft's own fumbling may help Linux. Its next  
generation operating software, Windows 2000, has been repeatedly 
delayed and isn't expected out until next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Moreover, Microsoft may shy away from a strong response to Linux  
during its epic antitrust trial. Federal prosecutors accuse 
Microsoft of abusing its software monopoly to squash competitors 
and are mulling ways to try to curb the company's power. 
</P>
<P>
	But some folks believe they've already found their Holy Grail.  
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that Linux represents the first substantial threat  
to Microsoft that we have seen yet,'' said magazine publisher Adam 
Goodman. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Goodman will introduce Linux Magazine with a  
decidedly confident cover: Half-crumbling letters casting dramatic 
shadows and spelling a lone word -- Microscared. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
