<HEADLINE> Colts To Sign Ex-Giant DE Bratzke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Indianapolis Colts have agreed to terms  
with former New York Giants defensive end Chad Bratzke in an effort 
to upgrade their sagging defense, team officials announced Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the deal were not disclosed. The Indianapolis Star and  
News reported today that Bratzke agreed to a multiyear contract 
paying him more than $5 million a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Bratzke, who became an unrestricted free agent this year, was  
the top DE in this year's market. He ranked eighth in the NFL with 
11.5 sacks last season and has started 42 of 50 games with the 
Giants since 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	He visited the Colts on Wednesday and has also met with Chicago,  
Tennessee and Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	Bratzke, 27, was taken by the Giants in the fifth round of the  
1994 draft out of Eastern Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colts have also signed former Carolina defensive end Shawn  
King and safety Chad Cota from New Orleans, reuniting both with 
Colts general manager Bill Polian, who drafted them while working 
as Panthers general manager. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colts have also added Vic Fangio as defensive coordinator  
and Michigan State assistant Tood Grantham as line coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart said the team also is interested in Atlanta linebacker  
Cornelius Bennett, although nothing has been finalized. Bennett was 
the Colts' top pick in the 1987 draft before being traded to the 
Buffalo Bills. 
</P>
