<HEADLINE> Tobacco Industry To Open Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- After nearly two months without a live witness and  
a 2 1/2-week break for the jury while attorneys argued over thousands 
of documents, the tobacco industry is set to defend itself in a 
landmark smoking case. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the first class-action lawsuit by smokers to reach trial.  
In this first phase, a jury will determine whether the defendants -- 
Philip Morris Inc., R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., and other cigarette 
makers and industry groups -- are responsible for injuries the 
plaintiffs claim they suffered because they were deceived into 
taking up a habit they couldn't quit. 
</P>
<P>
	If the tobacco companies are found liable, the jury will then  
decide which of the named plaintiffs should receive punitive 
damages. After that, other smokers could pursue their own trials. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense was scheduled to start its presentation Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	Edward L. Sweda, senior attorney with the Boston-based Tobacco  
Products Liability Project, said the industry lawyers won't be able 
to use some of their favorite defenses, such as blaming the smoker. 
</P>
<P>
	``The jury's focus, particularly in the initial phase, is on the  
industry's conduct,'' Sweda said. ``So (the industry is) in a very 
difficult position to try to explain away the long history of what 
they have done, and what their own documents spell out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The papers admitted include letters detailing attempts to  
influence scientists' interpretations of their research and figure 
out ways to keep negative findings from being used against the 
industry in court. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the trial began, the tobacco industry has already been  
dealt a blow via the Feb. 10 verdict in a California smoker's 
trial. Patricia Henley, a former three-pack-a-day smoker with 
inoperable lung cancer, contended Philip Morris had concealed the 
risks and addictiveness of smoking -- some of same issues raised in 
the Florida case. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors awarded Henley $51.5 million. Of that, $50 million was  
punitive damages, far exceeding the $15 million her attorneys had 
sought. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990228.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 13:14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Red Sox's Lowe Returns to Bullpen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- Derek Lowe is looking forward to  
pitching 70 games for the Red Sox this season. Just don't ask him 
to pitch the first inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowe, who came to Boston in a trade with Seattle midway through  
the 1997 season, has been dominating out of the bullpen but 
disappointing as a starter. 
</P>
<P>
	He says it's because he can't show hitters all his pitches on  
their first at-bat since they'll be used to his repertoire the next 
time around the lineup. Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan says it's 
because a starter needs three outstanding pitches and Lowe has just 
two -- a sinker and a curve. 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever the reason, Lowe was 0-7 with a 5.81 ERA in 10 starts  
last season and 3-2 with a 2.88 ERA and four saves in 53 relief 
appearances. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the beginning, I really enjoyed starting, but toward the  
end it was getting kind of monotonous with all the losing,'' Lowe 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston obtained Lowe from Seattle with catcher Jason Varitek for  
reliever Heathcliff Slocumb, who struggled and is now with 
Baltimore. Lowe, 25, and Varitek, 26, are two of Boston's most 
promising young players. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox have shown no desire to involve Lowe in another  
trade. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems to me any team I ever talked to in those winter  
meetings always seemed to want to bring up his name,'' Boston 
manager Jimy Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's good to be wanted, but you can't think about it too  
much,'' Lowe said. ``I'm happy they didn't trade me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was glad to leave Seattle where, he said, he didn't get the  
positive reinforcement that Williams and Kerrigan provide even when 
he struggles. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just felt somewhat of an outcast at times,'' Lowe said.  
``You'd have a bad game and no one would really say much to you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Lowe's sinker is so good that he led the majors last year  
with a ratio of allowing 4.58 ground balls to every fly ball. For 
every nine balls hit fairly, seven went on the ground. Terry Adams 
of the Chicago Cubs was a distant second at 2.82. Kerrigan says 
Lowe's ratio is the best since such statistics were first kept in 
1990. 
</P>
<P>
	``You bring him in in the middle of an inning with runners at  
first and third and one out or nobody out, you know you've got a 
good chance to get that double play,'' Kerrigan said. ``His sinker 
is very consistent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Varitek, who played with Lowe in the Seattle system, said,  
``when I first caught him he threw about 83, 84, 85 mph and now 
he's back up to 89, 90, 91. It makes a big difference when you've 
got his kind of sinker.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox wanted to use Lowe as a reliever but injuries forced  
him into a starting role last season and, after the sinker and 
curve, his third best pitch, the changeup, was inconsistent. He was 
back in the bullpen for good after his last start on June 28, a 5-1 
loss to Florida that dropped his record to 0-7. 
</P>
<P>
	He was outstanding the rest of the way. In the AL Division  
series, won by Cleveland 3-1, Lowe allowed one earned run in 4 1-3 
innings of relief. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every player wants to end the year on a high and I was able to  
do that,'' he said. ``When you've had success (as a reliever) 
you're comfortable in that role and, at the time, it was a good 
move to get me back into the role.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the unimpressive statistics as a starter, Kerrigan  
thinks Lowe benefited from that ordeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Starting really educated him,'' Kerrigan said. ``It threw all  
the variables at him that he had to know about growing up and 
learning how to be a pitcher in the big leagues, and the situations 
you're faced with that you have to come up with a plan for in the 
middle of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``When he went back to the bullpen, he became a better  
pitcher.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lowe and Jim Corsi are expected to share the middle relief and  
setup jobs for closer Tom Gordon, who was successful in 46 of his 
47 save opportunities. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just go as hard as you can, knowing you're not going to be  
out there for the long haul,'' Lowe said. ``I learned a lot last 
year so, hopefully, I can carry that over into this year.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
