<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 11:32:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Transplants May Help Brittle Bones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Imagine crossing your fingers for good luck only to crush your  
knuckles. Or, shrinking from a mother's embrace because she could 
snap your ribs with a loving hug. 
</P>
<P>
	For thousands of people with catastrophically brittle bones, the  
most routine movements can be life-threatening. 
</P>
<P>
	Now an experimental bone marrow transplant tried on three  
children with the crippling genetic disorder Osteogenesis 
Imperfecta has strengthened the youngsters' skeletons and reduced 
the frequency of debilitating fractures. 
</P>
<P>
	The transplant study appears in the March issue of the  
scientific journal Nature Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have not cured the disease,'' said Edwin Horwitz, who  
directed the experimental transplants. ``Our goal was to reduce the 
severity of their symptoms.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bone marrow transplantation is an arduous procedure most  
commonly used to kill late-stage cancers. After heavy doses of 
chemotherapy, patients are infused with stem cells that spawn new 
and healthy immune and blood cells. 
</P>
<P>
	The new method, tested at the St. Jude Children's Research  
Hospital in Memphis, Tenn., infused a different group of stem cells 
known as mesenchymal cells, or MSCs, that develop into bone and 
cartilage. 
</P>
<P>
	The therapy previously only had been tried in laboratory mice.  
</P>
<P>
	Conventional treatment of OI is limited to surgically implanting  
metal rods along the long bones of the arms and legs. 
</P>
<P>
	If it succeeds in larger trials, transplanting MSC cells would  
be the first long-term treatment of OI. 
</P>
<P>
	The bone marrow transplant also might be used to treat other  
bone, joint and growth deformities, including osteoporosis. 
</P>
<P>
	``MSC transplantation holds promise,'' said Stanton L. Gerson, a  
bone marrow transplantation specialist at Case Western Reserve 
University in Cleveland who reviewed the experiment. 
</P>
<P>
	The OI Foundation in Gaithersburg, Md., refused to comment on  
the study before its publication. 
</P>
<P>
	The disease is linked to abnormalities in genes responsible for  
the production of collagen, the fibrous protein that forms the 
body's bones and connective tissues. It's also affected by 
increased absorption of bone cells and slow bone formation. 
</P>
<P>
	One in 50,000 persons in the United States suffer from OI. In  
severe cases, patients may suffer hundreds of fractures in a 
lifetime. 
</P>
<P>
	Fetuses that develop OI in the womb rarely survive long after  
the trauma of birth. Youngsters with OI rarely grow more than 4 
feet tall and often are confined to wheelchairs. Most die early. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Memphis study, Horwitz and other researchers selected a  
girl and boy, both 13 months old, and a 32-month old boy for the 
transplants. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 13 months before their transplants, each of the patients  
had snapped bones at least three times; the infant girl suffered 37 
fractures. 
</P>
<P>
	Horwitz infused each child with MSC cells donated by healthy  
brothers and sisters. Within six months the conditions of the three 
children improved, although their progress varied. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990228.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 19:30:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flames Trade Fleury to Avalanche </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Theo Fleury, one of the NHL's top scorers, was  
traded from the Calgary Flames to Colorado on Sunday in a move the 
Avalanche hope will bolster their offense for the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Theo Fleury will bring some additional scoring punch to our  
hockey club and much more,'' coach Bob Hartley said. ``For many 
years in this league, he has been a proven leader and a great 
playoff performer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fleury, an unrestricted free agent at the end of the season,  
went to the Avalanche with winger Chris Dingman. The Flames 
received forward Rene Corbet, defenseman Wade Belak and future 
considerations. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleury, a 30-year-old wing, has spent his entire NHL career with  
the Flames, winning a Stanley Cup with the team as a rookie in 
1989. 
</P>
<P>
	He has 30 goals and 39 assists this season, ranking sixth in the  
NHL in scoring. He has said repeatedly he wouldn't sign a new 
contract until testing the free-agent market this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was an amazing opportunity that we couldn't let go by,''  
said Colorado general manager Pierre Lacroix. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Flames GM Al Coates didn't take issue with that.  
</P>
<P>
	``The Colorado Avalanche are a much better team today,'' he told  
The Canadian Press. ``Theo's a great player. We're going to miss 
him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fleury, who flew into Denver on Sunday night and was met by an  
impromptu welcoming party of media, fans and curious passengers at 
Denver International Airport, said he was ``shocked'' when he was 
informed of the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was tough, really tough'' to leave Calgary, he said. ``But  
I tell you, I was thrilled it was Colorado. They've got a great 
team. I think this is a great opportunity and a great situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he expected to be a rent-a-player for the playoffs or  
planned to be with Colorado beyond this season, he said, ``We'll 
see how it works out. My No. 1 focus is just hockey right now. The 
only reason why I'm here is to help this team win a Stanley Cup, 
and that's my intention. I don't think we need that distraction of 
me talking about my contract every day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Avalanche lead the NHL's Northwest Division with a 30-22-8  
record but have been inconsistent. They began the year with a 1-5-1 
record, then later ran off a 12-game winning streak that was 
followed immediately by an 0-3-4 stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	``Theo Fleury is an exciting player who will bring great energy  
to our club,'' Lacroix said. ``We were not the only NHL club 
interested in this type of player. We were able to make this deal 
mainly because of the depth in our organization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Fleury's acquisition, Lacroix said, ``I think we have the  
potential to reach the ultimate (Stanley Cup) this season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lacroix said he wasn't deterred by Fleury's contract status.  
</P>
<P>
	``We made this transaction purely on a hockey basis,'' he said.  
``The next few months will give us a chance to talk contract with 
Theo and his agent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fleury became the Flames' career scoring leader last Friday. In  
791 games, he has 364 goals and 466 assists for 830 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, Calgary's Cory Stillman said Fleury is ``by  
far our greatest player and he's proving it now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hartley said he hasn't decided which line Fleury will play on,  
but said the acquisition probably means the breakup of the Peter 
Forsberg-Joe Sakic pairing that has worked well for much of this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll take some time to see who plays better with whom,''  
Hartley said. ``We have to give the players time to get adjusted to 
Theo and for him to get adjusted to us. 
</P>
<P>
	``We gave up two good players and a future prospect, but that's  
the price you pay in this business. It's a great move.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sakic, who is a close friend of Fleury, said Fleury ``makes us  
that much better. I think what it really does is give us two solid 
lines. He's an exciting player who is great with the puck and is a 
spark plug out there. Obviously, we feel that with this trade we 
have a great chance to win the Stanley Cup. That's what this 
organization has always been about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Right wing Adam Deadmarsh called the trade ``definitely a  
shocker'' and said Fleury is ``one of the best players in the 
league -- one of the top 15 players, I'd say, for sure. Who wouldn't 
want him on their team?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defenseman Adam Foote said Fleury ``gives us two huge lines now  
and just strengthens the whole team. He's an offensive threat, a 
natural goal scorer, and he's also going to bring leadership and 
experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dingman, an enforcer, has played only two games this season.  
</P>
<P>
	Corbet, 25, has eight goals and 14 assists in 53 games but is  
currently sidelined with a strained hamstring. Belak, a 22-year-old 
prospect who was a No. 1 draft pick in 1994, had no points while 
appearing briefly in 22 games this season with the Avalanche. He 
currently is playing for Colorado's American Hockey League 
affiliate in Hershey, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleury's stance on free agency might explain why the Flames  
didn't get much in return for him. 
</P>
<P>
	While the trade immediately makes the Avalanche a serious  
Stanley Cup contender, it hurts the Flames (21-29-10) in the 
short-term. They are only two points behind Edmonton for the eighth 
and final playoff spot in the Western Conference, but now have lost 
their only true star. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
