<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Feb. 28, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Retired General Leads Nigeria Vote  
</P>
<P>
	ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- Retired Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo appears  
increasingly certain to win Nigeria's presidential vote. Election 
officials said Obasanjo had captured 62 percent of the vote with 31 
of Nigeria's 36 states and the federal capital reporting. Final 
results were not expected until tomorrow. Obasanjo's opponent, Olu 
Falae, the former finance minister, plans to contest the results. 
International observers reported ballot box-stuffing and other 
serious voting irregularities. Nigeria, Africa's most populous 
nation, has never held a presidential election in which the loser 
accepted defeat. 

</P>
<P>
	Senators Urge Preparation for Y2K  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate's leading experts on the Year 2000  
computer problem discounted doomsday scenarios but said today that 
it wouldn't hurt to put in a supply of food and water. Sens. Bob 
Bennett, R-Utah, and Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., who head a special 
Senate panel on the subject, said it could bring on real problems 
in this country, from electrical brownouts to breakdowns in medical 
equipment. But ``we will probably not have meltdown,'' Bennett 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	CDC Hosts Gulf War Illness Summit  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The federal government began a week-long  
conference today on ``Gulf War syndrome,'' where doctors, 
scientists and veterans' advocates hope to develop recommendations 
for future research. In the eight years since the Persian Gulf 
War's end, thousands of soldiers have complained of chronic, 
unexplained maladies such as fatigue, joint pain and memory loss. 
Researchers have been unable to scientifically link the symptoms of 
those who served in the 1991 war to any particular disease or 
biological agent. 

</P>
<P>
	Albright Plans To Rebuke China  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright arrived in  
China today planning to deliver a strong rebuke for a pattern of 
cracking down on political dissent. U.S. officials said China's 
lack of improvement on human rights could impede progress on 
Albright's primary mission, which is to talk to Chinese leaders 
about joining the World Trade Organization. Even as Albright 
arrived for the three-day visit, there was word of a renewed 
crackdown on dissidents. 

</P>
<P>
	Israelis Killed in Lebanon Bombing  
</P>
<P>
	MARJAYOUN, Lebanon (AP) -- Lebanese guerrillas detonated two  
bombs beside a military convoy today, killing a brigadier general 
and three other Israelis in one of the most serious attacks on 
Israel's forces in southern Lebanon. Brig. Gen. Erez Gerstein was 
the highest-ranking officer to die in Lebanon since the 1982 
Israeli invasion. Israel's top general said land, sea and air 
forces retaliated. Warplanes launched raids on suspected guerrilla 
hideouts in southern and eastern Lebanon. 

</P>
<P>
	Iraq: US Strikes Sever Oil Pipeline  
</P>
<P>
	BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- A U.S. airstrike damaged a pipeline in  
northern Iraq and halted the flow of oil, an Iraqi Oil Ministry 
official said today. American officials denied the charge. A 
Turkish official at the Ceyhan oil terminal confirmed that the flow 
had stopped and said an attack had hit energy transmission lines. 
Earlier today, U.S. fighter jets attacked Iraqi military 
installations after planes patrolling the ``no-fly'' zone over 
northern Iraq came under fire. 

</P>
<P>
	'8 MM' Leads Box Office  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``Eight Millimeter,'' a pornography thriller  
starring Nicolas Cage, pulled in $14.3 million in its opening 
weekend, topping all other movies at the box office. The Mel Gibson 
shoot-'em-up ``Payback'' made $6.9 million for second, while 
another debut, ``The Other Sister,'' with Juliette Lewis and 
Giovanni Ribisi in a love story about two mentally challenged 
people, opened in third place, with $6.7 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Maggert Wins Dramatic Match Play  
</P>
<P>
	CARLSBAD, Calif. (AP) -- Jeff Maggert showed the grit of a  
champion under the intense pressure today, chipping in for birdie 
on the 38th hole to beat Andrew Magee and win the Match Play 
Championship's $1 million first prize, the richest in tour history. 
Maggert is now 7-1 in match play as a professional, and the $1 
million is more than he has ever earned in any of his eight 
previous seasons on the PGA Tour. 

</P>
<P>
	No. 4 UConn Wins Big East  
</P>
<P>
	SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Richard Hamilton scored 26 points and  
Khalid El-Amin added 21 as No. 4 Connecticut ran past No. 24 
Syracuse 70-58 today to win the Big East championship outright for 
the fifth time in six seasons. The victory for Connecticut (25-2, 
16-2 Big East) gives the Huskies the top seed in the Big East 
tournament and leaves Syracuse (19-10, 10-8) with something to 
prove if it hopes to make the NCAA tournament. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
</P>
</TEXT>
