<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hungarian Premier Upbeat on Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) -- The Hungarian economy is expected to  
grow from 4 to 5 percent this year, Prime Minister Viktor Orban 
said on state-run radio Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	He spoke to reassure the public that the economy remains strong  
despite the sudden decision nine days earlier to freeze $222 
million in contingency spending. 
</P>
<P>
	That move came in reaction to the dramatic widening of the  
country's current account deficit, which was $2.3 billion in 1998, 
up from $981 million in 1997. The current account, a broad measure 
of trade, measures the difference between income from foreign 
sources and foreign obligations payable, excluding net capital 
investment. 
</P>
<P>
	On the issue of the need for a supplementary budget, Orban said  
first-quarter data and second-quarter trends must be studied before 
a decision is made. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the present economic situation, the ministries should not  
even think of getting supplementary funding,'' Orban said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
