<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Magee Has Week of Career  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARLSBAD, Calif. (AP) -- It was the week of Andrew Magee's  
career, though it ended abruptly with Jeff Maggert costing him 
$500,000 with one shot. 
</P>
<P>
	This was one second place finish he would savor.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a day I'll never forget,'' Magee said. ``This week was  
the best I've had on tour. I'll remember this even more than my 
wins.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Magee was disappointed that Maggert chipped in on the 38th  
hole of the day to win the $1 million first prize, he didn't show 
it a few minutes later as he sipped a light beer and looked back on 
a match that might have been. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, the $500,000 he pocketed for second helped ease the  
load. His biggest previous payday was $270,000 for winning the Las 
Vegas Invitational -- one of four career wins. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought about the money all day,'' Magee said. ``It's my  
biggest paycheck by double.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Magee could do nothing but watch with a wry grin on his face as  
Maggert's chip rattled into the hole for birdie on the par-3 11th 
for the win. 
</P>
<P>
	He had just missed a long putt for birdie himself and was  
already thinking about how he was going to play the next hole when 
the chip dropped. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ending was classic,'' Magee said. ``I even enjoyed it a  
little bit being the weirdo I am.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Magee, who had beaten five other opponents going into Sunday's  
final, would have been the first champion if the final had only 
gone 18 holes like all the other matches. 
</P>
<P>
	He was 3-up after nine holes and 2-up after 18, only to see his  
lead evaporate in the afternoon 18. By the time Maggert rolled in a 
short birdie putt on No. 13 the match was even, and they would both 
par the next six holes before Maggert's chip-in. 
</P>
<P>
	Magee just missed a 12-footer on the 17th hole to take the lead,  
then had a putt from the fringe on 18 come up just short. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I made the putt on 17,'' he said. ``And I thought I  
was going to hole out on the last hole. That was my mentality this 
week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ironically, the chip-in ended Magee's tournament just as he had  
ended John Huston's in the semifinals when he chipped in on the 
17th hole for a win. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no regrets,'' he said. ``I played as good as I could.  
That was a lot of golf.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed it was. Magee had played 126 holes when Maggert suddenly  
ended his bid for $1 million -- the biggest purse ever on the PGA 
tour. 
</P>
<P>
	The two players may not have been names like Tiger Woods and  
David Duval that tournament organizers hoped for in the finals, but 
they played a match that certainly surpassed expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	``They (fans) could just kind of put blinders on and think we  
were Tiger and Duval out there,'' Magee said. ``They wouldn't have 
known the difference.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
