<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shinn Accuser Wants Him Accountable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- The woman accusing Charlotte Hornets  
owner George Shinn of sexual assault at his South Carolina home in 
1997 says she's suing him to keep the millionaire businessman 
accountable. 
</P>
<P>
	``One day, I'll have to explain to my daughter what happened,''  
said Leslie Price, who agreed to identify herself publicly in an 
interview with The Charlotte Observer. ``What would I tell her if I 
didn't challenge him? That I gave in? That I let him get away with 
it? ... I can't let him do it again, not to me or anybody else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Price, 29, of Matthews, accuses Shinn in a Richland County,  
S.C., lawsuit of forcing her to perform oral sex at Shinn's 
mansion. Shinn, 57, has acknowledged having sex with Price but says 
it was consensual. Price is seeking unspecified damages. 
</P>
<P>
	Shinn was not charged with a crime. Prosecutors said there was  
not enough evidence to prove criminal charges. He declined to be 
interviewed for an Observer article published Sunday, but he issued 
a statement Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am truly sorry for the pain these false accusations have  
caused my family, friends, employees and our fans and community,'' 
Shinn said in the release. ``... There are those who will take 
extreme measures to discredit someone whose life is very public, 
and I am trying to cope with that in the right way. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thanks to my family, friends and a strong organization, I've  
begun to rebuild my life and will continue to do so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shinn's attorneys call Price a liar with a history of  
instability and an opportunist. Shinn has countersued in Charlotte, 
alleging he was slandered and targeted in a $5 million extortion 
plot. 
</P>
<P>
	Price, who was separated at the time of the encounter with  
Shinn, says she is now reunited with her husband, Jeff. They have a 
daughter. She's also free from a seven-year addiction to pain 
killers and says she nearly died during an overdose two months 
before meeting Shinn. 
</P>
<P>
	Price spends her days working with attorneys on her case and  
searching the Internet for information about Shinn. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure I'm the last person on earth George Shinn thought  
would stand up to him,'' she said. ``You don't want to look at it 
like a personal vendetta, but it is a vendetta. You can't get any 
more personal than this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit claims Shinn offered to introduce Price to a lawyer  
who could help her with child custody problems. The encounter 
occurred when Shinn drove her to his house in Tega Cay, S.C. 
instead of driving to a meeting with the attorney, according to 
Price. 
</P>
<P>
	Interviews by the Observer and investigative files show Shinn  
and Price tell vastly different stories, contradicting each other 
in almost every important detail. 
</P>
<P>
	Shinn paints Price as an eager, assertive sex partner. He did  
nothing, he says, that she might have misunderstood as force. Price 
recounts a violent, humiliating sex act. She struggled and 
screamed, she says, and Shinn could not have mistaken that for 
consent. 
</P>
<P>
	Price's lawsuit may go to trial this spring in Richland County.  
Both sides call an out-of-court settlement unlikely. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
