<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rep. Kasich Defends Friendship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful Rep. John  
Kasich, excluded from a California GOP convention because he 
offered to help a California Democrat, says more politicians should 
follow his example and put friendship ahead of politics. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich, R-Ohio, was not invited to speak at the convention  
because he offered to give a fund-raising dinner for Rep. Gary 
Condit, a conservative Democrat who represents a central California 
district in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gary is a good guy, and you know at times friendship ought to  
transcend party labels,'' Kasich said on ABC's ``This Week.'' 
``Gary Condit's one of my best friends in Congress, and he's one of 
the most conservative Democrats, and he's always helping us to cut 
taxes and to cut spending.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The dinner for Condit never occurred because Condit ``canceled  
it on me because he was afraid it was going to hurt me,'' Kasich 
said. ``That's the kind of friend you want in politics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said being passed over for a speaking slot at the state  
convention was ``not a big deal,'' adding that the California GOP 
``was flooded with calls from people saying, `If sometimes a 
politician can put friendship and principle above partisan 
politics, that's a good thing.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., former Vice President Dan Quayle,  
businessman Steve Forbes, former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and 
conservative commentator Alan Keyes were among potential 
presidential candidates who attended the conference in Sacramento. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
