<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 16:05:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mets Getting To Know Each Other </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. (AP) -- With so many new faces in the New  
York Mets' camp, several key players are spending spring training 
getting to know their neighbors. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides of the infield are making adjustments, now that  
Edgardo Alfonzo has shifted from third base to second. For 
shortstop Rey Ordonez, that means a new double-play partner in 
Alfonzo and a new third baseman in Robin Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Ordonez and Ventura) looked good. They looked like they could  
have fun together,'' manager Bobby Valentine said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Repetition is really key,'' he said. ``I can't really tell you  
what they need until maybe I see them in the regular season. It 
seems like it is going to be the regular stuff in spring 
training.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the addition of Bobby Bonilla and Rickey Henderson, the  
outfield is feeling its way through a new season as well. But 
Valentine was quick to point out that Henderson has free reign on 
any ball he can get to, including those tricky popups between the 
infielders and outfielders. 
</P>
<P>
	``Until Rey is going real full blast and Ricky's got his  
adrenaline going the range factor would be hard for them to 
determine,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets will have another special visitor at their complex  
Monday in Hall of Fame pitcher Tom Seaver. 
</P>
<P>
	Seaver, who will broadcast his former team's games this season,  
also signed to help the Mets pitchers in spring training. 
</P>
<P>
	Valentine said he had no idea who Seaver would work with or what  
he would do, but added he thought starter Rick Reed and minor 
leaguer Dan Murray had styles similar to Seaver. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Hall of Famer Sandy Koufax visited camp and worked  
with the pitchers, especially Al Leiter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
