<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Celebrity Inmate Back in Spotlight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANGOLA, La. (AP) -- The pressure of success is growing on the  
editor of one of Louisiana's most honored publications. Wilbert 
Rideau is juggling even more calls, visits, obligations -- lately 
because of his work on a film that is nominated for an Oscar. 
</P>
<P>
	But he is relaxed. He has years to get his work done. Maybe a  
lifetime. 
</P>
<P>
	``Prison keeps you real,'' said the editor of The Angolite  
magazine. ``It focuses your attention and shows you how little is 
really a necessary part of life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He should know. At the age of 57, Rideau has been a resident of  
Louisiana State Prison at Angola for 38 years. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1961, when he was just 19, Rideau robbed a bank and took  
three hostages. While they begged for their lives, he shot them. 
One of the victims fell into a bayou and escaped. One, shot in the 
neck, feigned death. The third tried to crawl away and Rideau 
stabbed her and slashed her throat. 
</P>
<P>
	While waiting to die in the electric chair, Rideau was reborn.  
Unlike most death-row conversions, however, words became his 
salvation, not religion; he taught himself to read and began 
writing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't want a criminal act to be the final definition of  
me,'' Rideau said. ``I picked up a pen and tried to do something 
good. It allowed me to weave meaning into what would have been a 
meaningless existence. It also gave me a chance to try to make 
amends.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1972 the U.S. Supreme Court struck down Louisiana's death  
penalty and Rideau was re-sentenced to life. 
</P>
<P>
	Refused a job by the then all-white staff of the prison  
magazine, The Angolite, Rideau started his own publication, The 
Lifer, and began writing a weekly column for a chain of black 
newspapers. In 1976 he was named editor of The Angolite and 
transformed it from a mimeographed newsletter into a slick 
bimonthly magazine that has won a string of awards. 
</P>
<P>
	A typical day last week saw Rideau preparing for visitors from  
Emory University journalism school and the Southwestern Louisiana 
criminal justice classes. Celebrity lawyer Johnnie Cochran was 
expected, Time Magazine was phoning, The New York Times was back 
for a second day of interviews. On top of that he had a magazine to 
get out and was trying to sell another film. 
</P>
<P>
	This recent attention comes for his work helping to direct the  
Oscar-nominated documentary ``The Farm,'' which also won last 
year's prize for documentaries at the Sundance Film Festival. 
</P>
<P>
	Previously, he was named ABC News' ``Person of the Week'' in  
1992, profiled in Life Magazine in 1993. He wrote and narrated an 
award-winning National Public Radio documentary, did a television 
documentary and collaborated on a film about an execution for the 
Discovery Channel. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Rideau bills himself as ``The Most Rehabilitated Prisoner in  
America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But despite his impressive resume, he still earns 20 cents an  
hour, sleeps on a narrow metal bunk in a 74-man dormitory, and must 
get permission and a guard to move around on prison grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``No matter what I do or what awards or honors I get, this is  
still prison,'' Rideau said. ``And the key to getting out of prison 
is anonymity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He's not the only one who believes his accomplishments are the  
reason he's still locked up. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were 13 men on death row when Wilbert Rideau got  
there,'' said Ted Quant, director of the Twomey Center for Peace 
Through Justice at Loyola University and the Rideau Project they 
run. ``Every one of them was released except Wilbert Rideau. There 
were 31 murderers sent to Angola in 1962; all but Wilbert Rideau 
have regained their freedom. But you never heard of any of those 
others.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's what bothers Rideau most.  
</P>
<P>
	``If all those people were still in prison I'd say what's  
happened to me is fair,'' he said. ``But they aren't. I get post 
cards from a former inmate who killed four people. He's out and I'm 
not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rideau has gained Pardon Board recommendations for release since  
1984, but so far four governors have refused, including Edwin 
Edwards who pardoned 89 murderers before leaving office in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``The nature of the crime he committed was so unnecessary I can  
only believe it happened from some mental lapse,'' Edwards said. 
``I was just afraid if he was released to society it might happen 
again. ...'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Rideau's accomplishments don't sway Louisiana's current  
governor. 
</P>
<P>
	``The governor will tell you very quickly that prison is for  
punishment,'' said Cheney Joseph, executive counsel to Gov. Mike 
Foster. ``I don't think anyone these days would tell you it's about 
rehabilitation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rideau remains optimistic.  
</P>
<P>
	``I still believe I'll get out someday,'' he said. ``Of course,  
all prisoners believe that. You have to or you couldn't get up 
every day and go on.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
