<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WNBA Player Leaves Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Houston Comets point guard Kim Perrot walked away  
from the hospital Sunday morning, four days after doctors removed a 
golf ball-sized cancerous tumor from just below the surface of her 
brain. 
</P>
<P>
	``This first part of this journey has been successful,'' Perrot  
said at a news conference shortly before her discharge from the 
University of Texas M.D. Anderson Cancer Center. ``I feel like I 
can run around and play basketball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perrot's steps were slow but sure. She wore a WNBA championship  
hat to conceal the scar on the left side of her head. 
</P>
<P>
	On Feb. 19, doctors told Perrot that it was a brain tumor  
causing the recent weakness in her right arm and headaches. Worse, 
three weeks of testing had revealed the tumor was caused by 
spreading lung cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Perrot, 32, is scheduled to begin 2 1/2 weeks of radiation therapy  
next Monday to eradicate several smaller tumors in her head. Then 
she'll immediately start six months of chemotherapy to attack the 
lung cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Physically, she's in excellent condition,'' said Perrot's  
radiation oncologist, Dr. Ritsuko Komaki. ``I do not expect any 
problems during radiation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perrot might be able to at least suit up with the Comets this  
summer if she responds well to chemotherapy, doctors have said. 
</P>
<P>
	As expected, the large brain tumor was located perilously close  
to the motor cortex of the brain that provides strength to Perrot's 
right hand and arm. Dr. Raymond Sawaya had to remove the cancer 
from between two folds of the brain. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was very delicate because of the location of the tumor,''  
said Sawaya, who had to be worried about applying too much pressure 
to the brain while extracting the growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Perrot proudly made several clinched fists for television  
cameras Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like I have not lost any strength in my hand,'' she  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Perrot, supported by visiting family members from her hometown  
of Lafayette, La., and elsewhere, said she's been overwhelmed by 
cards, letters and e-mails from fans around the world. But 
basketball has dominated her thoughts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think about it every day. It's what I've been doing all my  
life and I've made a career out of it,'' said Perrot, who rose from 
obscurity to help lead Houston to the WNBA's first two titles. ``To 
think that could be taken away was hard to deal with. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I'm going to be playing basketball again.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
