<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grudzielanek Poised for Comeback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VERO BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Mark Grudzielanek got very tired of  
hearing about his defensive deficiencies. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's annoying,'' Grudzielanek said after Sunday's workout at  
Dodgertown. ``It really is. But on the other hand it's something I 
needed to get better at.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So instead of sitting around and sulking during the offseason,  
the Dodgers shortstop, who committed 33 errors last year and 32 the 
previous year, did something about it -- he worked all winter with 
Bucky Dent at the former major league shortstop's baseball school 
in Boca Raton. 
</P>
<P>
	``We pretty much had a total tuneup,'' said Grudzielanek, a Palm  
Beach resident. ``We went through footwork, throwing -- where I 
place the ball in my hand -- double plays. It was more talking about 
it than anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grudzielanek, who was traded to the Dodgers from the Montreal  
Expos along with Carlos Perez and Hiram Bocachica for Wilton 
Guerrero, Ted Lilly, Peter Bergeron and Jon Tucker last July 31, 
has always put up solid numbers offensively. 
</P>
<P>
	After working with Dent, he's confident he now has the glove to  
go along with his bat. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully this will be the last year anybody says anything bad  
about my defense,'' said Grudzielanek, who lost his arbitration 
case this winter. He will make $1.9 million instead of the $2.6 
million he was seeking. 
</P>
<P>
	There was nothing but praise for Grudzielanek when he got to the  
majors in 1995 with the Expos. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a fine hitter,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``He  
has a lot of power for a shortstop and he usually hits what he 
swings at. But I thought he was a little too pull conscious last 
year, and I'd like to see him use the whole field more. If he can 
do that, I think he'll have a big year for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, Grudzielanek's first full season in the majors, he hit  
.306 with six home runs with 49 RBIs and 33 steals, earning him a 
trip to the All-Star game. Although he committed 27 errors, the 
future looked bright and nobody was questioning his defensive 
ability. 
</P>
<P>
	Then things started to go downhill quickly.  
</P>
<P>
	His relationship with team officials were strained after a  
contract squabble in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a new start for me,'' Grudzielanek said. ``I'm happier  
here with the Dodgers, I'm healthy, and I'm going to be playing on 
grass. With all those factors going in my favor I think this will 
be a good year for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grudzielanek, who has always been secure about his job status in  
past training camps, still has to beat out Jose Vizcaino for the 
starting shortstop job this spring, but he appears to be the clear 
favorite. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I've done the last few years speak for themselves,''  
Grudzielanek said. ``I'm not worrying about (the competition). I'm 
going to do what I've done the previous spring -- getting myself 
ready for April.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
