<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chicago's City News Closing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- After more than a century of chronicling  
politics, murder and mayhem in Chicago, the City News Bureau is 
closing its doors forever. 
</P>
<P>
	The City News, a gritty training ground for cub reporters for  
108 years, had a skeleton crew at work Sunday in its downtown 
office, monitoring phones, the morgue, police and fire scanners. 
</P>
<P>
	At midnight, the office would be shuttered for good.  
</P>
<P>
	The bureau's joint owners, the Chicago Tribune and the Chicago  
Sun-Times, announced in October that it was no longer financially 
viable to keep the service open. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, a coalition of 10 Chicago news operations has  
stepped in to create a replacement wire service. The New City News 
Bureau, a streamlined version of the old one, will begin operations 
out of Chicago Tribune offices on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The closing marks an end to an era in journalism, said Paul  
Zimbrakos, who as managing editor has headed City News for more 
than 30 years and started out as a copy boy there 41 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's sad. For 108 years City News trained hundreds and  
hundreds of reporters,'' said Zimbrakos. He estimated he has 
handled more than 30,000 homicide stories and 72 elections since 
1958. 
</P>
<P>
	Since City News opened its doors in 1890, the service has  
provided news 24 hours a day, seven days a week, to Chicago's major 
newspapers and other subscribers, including The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	It paid reporters shoestring salaries, as editors and rewrite  
staff intimidated, cajoled and often coerced their young charges 
into getting the news. 
</P>
<P>
	Many City News veterans, like the late Pulitzer Prize-winning  
columnist Mike Royko, went on to work for Chicago's daily 
newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	Other alumni include novelist Kurt Vonnegut, journalist Seymour  
Hersh, and playwright Charles MacArthur, who based ``The Front 
Page,'' the play he wrote with Ben Hecht, in part on his experience 
as a City News reporter. 
</P>
<P>
	During a farewell party Friday night, some of Chicago's  
best-known reporters recalled witnessing grisly scenes and running 
to the nearest pay phone to call in their scoops. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where are the bodies? I'm from City News,'' Chicago Sun-Times  
reporter Charles Nicodemus said he told a police officer after 
arriving by bus at his first murder scene. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
