<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Inch Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar fell against the yen on profit-taking in  
early trading Monday, while Japanese stock prices inched higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 119.12 yen, down 1.20 yen from late Friday in  
Tokyo and slightly below its New York level of 119.17 yen late 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 36.51 points  
or 0.25 percent, to 14,404.05 in the first 30 minutes of trading. 
On Friday, the index shed 102.91 points, or 0.71 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar faced sell orders from domestic  
exporters wanting to take take profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Many investors remained on the sidelines ahead of high-level  
talks on economic deregulation between Japan and the United States, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were alert to comments from finance officials during  
the talks and also watched a World Bank symposium on global finance 
and development, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 131.13 yen, down  
from 132.35 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices rose despite Friday's decline on  
Wall Street. Traders said encouraging Japanese economic data 
prompted expectations the nation's economy may be starting to 
bottom out. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the Ministry of International Trade and Industry said  
Japan's industrial production rose a larger-than-expected 0.8 
percent in January, climbing for the second straight month. MITI 
also forecast output would continue to rise in February and March. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average fell 59.76 points to 9,306.58  
on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 0.12 points, or 0.01 percent, to 1,120.15. The 
TOPIX lost 4.10 points, or 0.36 percent, Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government  
bond was unquoted early Monday after finishing Friday at 1.885 
percent and a price of 99.32 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
