<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Feb. 28, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Ex-General Leads Nigeria Elections  
</P>
<P>
	ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- Early poll results this morning gave  
retired Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo the lead in two states and the 
capital in Nigeria's presidential elections. Marking the final 
phase of democracy's return to Africa's most populous nation, tens 
of millions of Nigerians turned out at polls yesterday in the 
long-awaited election. Many hope the event will sweep aside 15 
years of corrupt and brutal military rule. The race pits Obasanjo, 
a former military ruler seeking a civilian comeback 20 years after 
leaving power, against former finance minister Olu Falae. 

</P>
<P>
	Clintons To Rest in Utah  
</P>
<P>
	PARK CITY, Utah (AP) -- President Clinton and his family are in  
Utah for a reunion to celebrate daughter Chelsea's 19th birthday. 
The Clintons are borrowing the mountaintop home of Hollywood 
executive Jeffrey Katzenberg for their Utah vacation. They'll stay 
there until Tuesday. The president was greeted by Utah Governor 
Mike Leavitt and other lawmakers after Air Force One landed in Salt 
Lake City. Leavitt says Clinton, who has skied only once before, 
does not plan a second adventure on the slopes. Instead, he plans 
to read. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Monitors Tail Yugoslav Army  
</P>
<P>
	SUVA REKA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Bright orange vehicles of  
international monitors cruised the back roads of Kosovo yesterday, 
tailing Yugoslav army tanks and armored personnel carriers to 
prevent attacks against ethnic Albanians. Violence between the two 
sides has been increasing in the weeks before U.S.-led peace talks 
resume March 15. There are fears that scattered attacks on the eve 
of the war's anniversary could blossom into a new Yugoslav 
offensive. 

</P>
<P>
	Defibrillator Training Launched  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The American Red Cross launches a program this  
week to train everyday Americans to jump-start the hearts of 
cardiac arrest victims. Red Cross officials hope to put the power 
of lifesaving defibrillators in more hands across the nation. While 
CPR buys patients crucial time, it will not restart a heart. Now 
companies, shopping malls, even amusement parks are buying portable 
defibrillators, small versions of the electric shock paddles made 
famous on TV, that can jolt hearts into beating again. Experts say 
portable defibrillators could save 100,000 lives a year. 

</P>
<P>
	2 Mir Crew Members Return to Earth  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- A Russian and a Slovak returned safely from the  
Mir space station early this morning. The duo landed their Soyuz 
capsule in the plains of northern Kazakstan, officials said. 
Russian Gennady Padalka, the Mir's commander for the past six 
months, and Slovak Ivan Bella, who had been on the Mir for just 
under a week, touched down early this morning, said a spokesman at 
Mission Control in Moscow. Their departure from Mir leaves three 
men aboard who may be the last crew on the 13-year-old space 
station. 

</P>
<P>
	Gadhafi May Refuse Lockerbie Deal  
</P>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi appeared to  
pull back yesterday from a U.N.-brokered compromise on the 1988 Pan 
Am bombing case. In a joint statement issued in Tripoli with 
visiting Namibian President Sam Nujoma, Gadhafi said the 
International Court of Justice at The Hague, Netherlands, was the 
proper venue for the case -- rather than a Scottish court sitting in 
the Netherlands. On Friday, the United States and Britain gave 
Libya a one-month deadline to turn over the suspects. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan To Conduct Heart Transplant  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A team of doctors assembled today for Japan's first  
heart transplant in more than three decades after a hospital 
declared a comatose woman brain-dead. The 44-year-old woman's heart 
and lungs will be sent by helicopter to a university hospital in 
Osaka, where a patient is waiting to receive the organs. Another 
patient was to receive the woman's liver. The woman is the first 
person carrying a valid donor's card to be declared brain-dead 
since a new law in 1997 allowed doctors to make the diagnosis. 

</P>
<P>
	Venus, Coetzer Advance to Finals  
</P>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Top-seeded defending champion Venus  
Williams moved into the final of the IGA SuperThrift Tennis Classic 
by beating qualifier Lilia Osterloh 6-2, 6-3 last night. Williams, 
ranked No. 5 in the world, needed 61 minutes to advance opposite 
No. 3 Amanda Coetzer, who beat flu-ridden Anna Kournikova 6-4, 6-2 
in the other semifinal. 

</P>
<P>
	Mighty Ducks 4, Sharks 1  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Teemu Selanne scored the 300th goal of  
his NHL career and later added three assists as the Anaheim Mighty 
Ducks beat the San Jose Sharks 4-1 last night. With a first-period 
goal in his 464th game, Selanne became the sixth fastest player in 
league history to reach the 300 mark. Only Wayne Gretzky, Mario 
Lemieux, Brett Hull, Mike Bossy and Jari Kurri have reached it in 
fewer games. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
