<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 08:32:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jagge Wins Slalom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OFTERSCHWANG, Germany (AP) -- Finn Christian Jagge won his second  
slalom race this season convincing fashion, and Norwegian teammate 
Andre Aamodt vaulted to the top of the World Cup overall standings 
with a third-place finish Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jagge skied down a course made difficult by soft snow in 1  
minute 47.76 seconds for his two runs in the first World Cup event 
held in this resort. He flashed across the finish line 1.05 seconds 
ahead of Austrian Thomas Stangassinger, who took a big step toward 
wrapping up the slalom title. 
</P>
<P>
	``The slope was a little fast and a little slippery, but it was  
good for me,'' said Jagge, 32, who won his sixth career slalom 
title. ``I've had a difficult year, but now I'm happy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aamodt's third-place finish gave him 1,130 points in the overall  
race, allowing him to pass Austria's Hermann Maier at 1,103 and 
fellow Norwegian Lasse Kjus, who has 1,089. Kjus was the leader 
before sitting sat out the weekend's races with the flu. 
</P>
<P>
	Aamodt was third in 1:49.13, denying Bode Miller a podium spot  
by just nine-hundredths. The American was fourth, but had the 
fastest second run of 54.48 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller said his surprising eighth-place finish in the world  
championships three weeks ago in Vail, Colo., bolstered his 
confidence. He put together one of the best placings by any U.S. 
men's skier this season. 
</P>
<P>
	No American has won a World Cup slalom since 1983.  
</P>
<P>
	Stangassinger built his leading total in the season slalom race  
to 466 points. Jure Kosir of Slovenia, who settled for sixth place 
Sunday, is second with 391. 
</P>
<P>
	Stangassinger now just needs a 10th-place finish in the final  
slalom event -- next month in Sierra Nevada, Spain -- to wrap up the 
title. 
</P>
<P>
	For Stangassinger, the race was revenge for the way outsiders  
swept the top three spots at the worlds under icy conditions in the 
event, leaving the proven slalom skiers behind. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jagge, who was unbeatable today, me and Aamodt were out front.  
In Vail, we were the victims of the ice -- now we've shown what we 
can do, under fair conditions,'' Stangassinger said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jagge led after the first run in 53.28, then used his experience  
to slide through the ruts left by the previous skiers to finish 
second behind Miller at 54.48 on the next go-around despite 
starting last among the top racers. 
</P>
<P>
	Kalle Palander of Finland, the surprise gold medalists at the  
worlds, was disqualified on the first run after skidding by a gate. 
Austrian rookie sensation Benjamin Raich, who has claimed two 
slaloms this year, suffered the same fate on his second run to 
spoil his 21st birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	Palander's gold at the worlds, the first by a Finish skier, had  
electrified his country. But he again failed to win a World Cup 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a stupid mistake, just stupid,'' Palander said. ``I  
came at the gates too directly, then was leaning too far back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lead in the battle between Aamodt, Kjus and Maier traded  
hands twice in as many days. Maier had seized first place in the 
standings by finishing fourth in Saturday's giant slalom behind 
countryman Stephan Eberharter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
