<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cherry Growers Invest in Boiler / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASCO, Wash. (AP) -- Ami and Dave MacHugh hope to protect their  
cherries from spring frost by firing up a huge boiler that should 
make their orchard warm and steamy. 
</P>
<P>
	They got the idea from the Washington Public Power Supply System  
nuclear power plant, across the Columbia River from their orchard. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just looking across the river at that steam plume every day,  
we thought we needed to capture that and bring it over here when 
it's cold out,'' said Ami MacHugh, president of the Franklin County 
Farm Bureau. 
</P>
<P>
	The MacHughs unloaded the 90,000-pound blue boiler last week. It  
was a castoff from a nuclear submarine base. 
</P>
<P>
	They would not say how much it cost, but they spent $26,000 to  
transport it across from Connecticut on a flatbed truck. 
</P>
<P>
	Much is at stake, said Robert Evans, agricultural engineer at  
the Prosser agricultural research station. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because of the tremendous economic consequences of not  
protecting, producers in the region have established one of the 
most extensive, elaborate and expensive frost-protection networks 
in the world,'' Evans said. 
</P>
<P>
	Costs can range from $400 to $15,000 an acre.  
</P>
<P>
	The MacHughs' diesel-powered boiler heats 40-degree Columbia  
River water to 100 degrees at a rate of 1,800 gallons per minute. 
The water then is sprayed around the orchard through irrigation 
lines that run underneath the mature, high-value trees. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, we could make fog,'' Ami MacHugh said.  
</P>
<P>
	The MacHughs' boiler, about 15 feet high and 30 feet long, is  
sitting on a concrete pad in the middle of the orchard. 
</P>
<P>
	Plans are to heat enough water to cover half of the 100-acre  
orchard with the 2,000-horsepower boiler. With luck, wind will blow 
the warmed air over the rest of the trees, Dave MacHugh said. 
</P>
<P>
	The application should raise the orchard's air temperature a few  
degrees to keep the buds from freezing and dying. Just a degree or 
two can make the difference between a lost crop and a profit of 
several hundred thousand dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans has spent the past five years testing a similar, much  
smaller system on two acres in Prosser. He found it to be six or 
seven times more efficient than the old-fashioned smudge pots that 
burn oil in canisters to heat orchard air. 
</P>
<P>
	``It works very well,'' Evans said. ``The disadvantage of this  
is it's very expensive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the McHughs' system proves itself, more farmers will try it,  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are running out of options in a lot of ways,'' Evans said.  
``When you have $10,000 to $15,000 invested per acre, you can 
almost not afford not to heat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smudge pots are on the way out because of the smoke they  
produce. Some farmers are turning to propane-fired heaters or 
installing overhead sprinklers in new orchards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
