<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vinny Castilla Is Jordan of Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Vinny Castilla has supplanted Fernando  
Valenzuela as the Michael Jordan of Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's like the president out there,'' said Colorado Rockies  
outfielder Curtis Goodwin, who played with Castilla in the Mexican 
winter league. ``He's probably bigger than the president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Castilla-mania promises to grow exponentially in the next month  
as the Rockies prepare to play baseball's season opener April 4 in 
Monterrey, Mexico. It's a date Castilla has circled on his 
calendar. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm so excited about this game,'' he said Sunday. ``It's going  
to be in front of my people. They've followed me all through my 
career. ... People love me over there. I love them, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Castilla, who has hit at least 40 home runs in three straight  
seasons, is Mexico's biggest baseball star since Valenzuela started 
throwing his screwball for the Los Angeles Dodgers nearly 20 years 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's No. 1 in Mexico right now,'' said Roberto Ramirez, a  
Colorado pitcher who played for Mexico City from 1991-97. 
``Fernando Valenzuela was a big man in Mexico. Right now, It's 
Vinny Castilla -- in all parts of Mexico.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Castilla has willingly embraced the role, returning home each  
year to make an appearance in the Mexican winter league. He did not 
disappoint in 1998 despite playing all 162 games for the Rockies 
before traveling to Japan with a group of major league stars in 
November. 
</P>
<P>
	``One month's enough for me to rest,'' Castilla said. ``I just  
love the game so much. People ask me, `What's your hobby? Do you 
play golf?' My hobby's baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Drafted by the Rockies in the 1992 expansion draft, Castilla's  
dedication has helped transform him from a scrawny infielder in the 
Atlanta Braves organization into a two-time All-Star who has 
surpassed Colorado's modest expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt he had the potential to be a 20, 25 home run guy,''  
Rockies general manager Bob Gebhard said. ``He's just gotten bigger 
and stronger and better each and every year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After hitting 32 homers as Colorado's full-time third baseman in  
1994, Castilla hit 40 homers and 113 RBIs in each of the next two 
seasons. He was rewarded with a four-year, $24 million contract and 
responded by hitting 46 homers and driving in 144 runs. 
</P>
<P>
	Considered a bargain at today's free-agent prices, Castilla  
shows no sign of slowing down. He has played in 247 straight games 
and 620 of the last 630. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a blue-collar worker's dream,'' Colorado hitting  
instructor Clint Hurdle said. ``Every day he shows up, it's a brand 
new day. I don't think he knows when he's in a slump because ... 
his best recollection is yesterday, if he even goes back that far. 
He's always looking forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though he doesn't dwell on the past, Castilla will never forget  
falling in love with baseball while growing up in Oaxaca, Mexico. 
His dad played in the Mexican League, prompting Castilla to take up 
the game. 
</P>
<P>
	His talent led to a contract with the Braves, who bounced him  
between Atlanta and the minors before leaving him unprotected in 
the expansion draft. 
</P>
<P>
	The road will come full circle when the Rockies and San Diego  
Padres play before a sellout crowd in Monterrey. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I've come a long way,'' Castilla said. ``I never  
thought I was going to be a big league player. I've come a long 
way, man, a long way.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
