<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Senator Urges Stand on Abortion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Republican activists have ended a  
state party convention that featured a leadership fight centered on 
the candidates' abortion stances. Now, they are ready to return to 
their real business -- defeating Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	``Compared to the differences between us and the Democrats, the  
differences between one Republican and another are minor,'' 
convention delegate Adam Fogerson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP's dislike for President Clinton emerged as a unifying  
factor at the semiannual weekend gathering that featured 
appearances by seven White House hopefuls. It was a reflection of 
the new clout in presidential politics that comes with California's 
earlier-than-ever primary next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire and former Vice President Dan  
Quayle both drew standing ovations when they praised the House 
trial managers who fought to remove Clinton from office following 
his impeachment. Smith said the president ``behaves like an 
animal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While all seven GOP aspirants oppose abortion, their political  
handling of the issue mirrored the split in the party. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith made a fire-and-brimstone presentation of his  
anti-abortion stance. 
</P>
<P>
	``Killing children is the central issue facing our nation today,  
and it needs to be stopped,'' he said. ``If we're not going to 
stand up for the life of unborn children, maybe the Republican 
Party deserves to fall into the ash bin of history ... and it will, 
if we don't stand up for life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others, like former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, echoed those  
who called for the party to emphasize less-divisive issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``Instead of laying down litmus tests and rigid pronouncements,  
reach out to others with whom we agree,'' he urged convention 
attendees. 
</P>
<P>
	The California GOP suffered devastating losses in November's  
election, with just two Republicans holding statewide offices. That 
upped the ante for pulling the party together at the convention. 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Schnur, a GOP consultant, said he came in bracing for a  
``circular firing squad'' but witnessed merely ``a water balloon 
fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This party did what you're supposed to do when you're looking  
to get back on track -- it argued its differences and put them aside 
and moved on,'' he said. ``We're not going to solve them at a 
convention.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whether or not the party emerges from its convention truly  
unified remains to be seen, but Republicans were clearly happy to 
get past the battle for the state party chairmanship. 
</P>
<P>
	The victor, former party Vice Chairman John McGraw, has said  
banning abortion is his No. 1 mission; his opponent, Nicholas 
Bavaro, said he would have focused on other issues. McGraw won 
decisively. 
</P>
<P>
	He preached harmony in his victory speech, and sought to rally  
the Republicans around the cause of beating Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want this to be the party of open and honest debate,'' he  
told the delegates. ``But when that is done, I want us to unite and 
go after the Democrats.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
